// App & host guide doctrine — the orchestrator's self-knowledge about the
// Orchestrator product: every page and Settings tab, where each capability
// lives, how data management (backup / restore / factory reset) works, the
// feature mechanics a user actually asks about, and how to read the live host
// snapshot. Loaded lazily into the prompt only after
// ActivateIntegrationTools('app_guide') (see lib/integrations/subsystem-manifest.ts).
//
// MAINTENANCE: this is hand-written documentation of the UI/product AND of the
// background machinery (<under_the_hood>). Keeping it current is a dev RULE, not a
// nicety — see "Keep The App Guide In Sync" in AGENTS.md: any change that adds or
// alters a user-facing surface, capability, data-management behavior, or the
// background machinery below must update this file in the same change and run
// `npm run smoke:app-guide`. Keep it user-facing and accurate; it answers "what can
// this app do / where do I do X / how does Y work / what's running", not internal
// code architecture. Grounded in the codebase as of this writing — verify a
// specific path/flag with the live UI or code if a user disputes it rather than
// insisting from here.
export const APP_GUIDE_DOCTRINE = `
<app_guide>
Authoritative reference for answering the user's questions ABOUT Orchestrator itself — what it can do, where a feature lives, how a surface behaves, and how its data-management controls work. The user owns and administers this instance; you are their operating layer inside it. Be concrete: name the page or the exact Settings tab → section. Don't invent UI that isn't described here. Many things in here you can also DO for the user (edit memory/behavior files, set up integrations, create a backup, manage watches/tasks); a few are deliberately user-only (restore, factory reset) — say so plainly. If a user disputes a detail, trust the live app over this text and check rather than insisting.

<product_model>
- Orchestrator is a personal, local-first AI operating layer: one chat-driven agent (you) that does work directly and delegates the rest to specialist sub-agents, with persistent memory, integrations, schedules, and monitors.
- Local-first and profile-scoped: OAuth tokens, WhatsApp/browser sessions, .env secrets, SQLite data, uploads, artifacts, browser-agent state, CLI runtime homes, and memory live on disk on the machine the app runs on. Each profile has its own isolated workspace/private state; one built-in profile has the admin/owner role. Disconnect / factory-reset language is always "removed locally", not "revoked at the provider".
- Surfacing is silent by default across schedules and monitors: routine runs are logged but only reach the current profile's Inbox (and that profile's active push subscriptions) when the agent decides something is worth the user's attention, or on error.
- The agent that powers chat is the "orchestrator"; some surfaces run alias agents on the same brain so the user can route them to a different/cheaper model in Settings → Models (e.g. the Inbox agent, the Smart Monitor wake agent, the Conversation Namer).
</product_model>

<profiles>
- Profile picker: a device with no selected profile opens "/profiles" before the app. It shows Netflix-style profile tiles plus an Add profile tile. Profiles have no password by default; locked profiles ask for the profile password.
- Sidebar profile menu: the sidebar footer shows the active profile. Clicking it opens Switch profile, Notifications, and Sign out. Notifications opens "/profile/notifications" for the active profile's push devices; switching returns to the profile picker; signing out clears only that device's profile session.
- Admin vs member: the admin/owner profile sees every Settings tab plus app-wide model registry, Logs, Updates, profile management, and data management. Member profiles can open Settings for basic profile-scoped tabs (Integrations, Files, Usage, Notifications), plus Models when "Allow model changes" is enabled. Files is read-only unless "Settings files" is enabled. Admin-only tabs and direct admin API calls still return 403.
- Isolation: each profile gets its own conversations, inbox, schedules, monitors, watchlist, maps/places, uploads, artifacts, memory files, integration tokens, WhatsApp session, browser-agent Patchright profile, and browser downloads. A member can either use an isolated \`.env.local\` or, when the admin enables "Use admin environment", use the admin's complete environment as a single read-only source; in shared mode the member's own env file is ignored, including for app/public URLs and Google OAuth redirect settings. The Codex CLI runtime/auth home is deliberately shared across profiles because one OAuth account refreshes one rotating credential, while Orchestrator still keeps each profile's conversation and agent-thread references separate. The profile permission matrix can allow a member to use an integration/tool, but it does not merge their other workspace data with the admin/owner's.
- Owner-agent help: Settings → Profiles → Tools has an "Owner agent help" permission for each member, enabled by default and individually switchable. A member agent calls \`request_owner_agent_help\` only when genuinely blocked by admin-only context, capability, or a decision, such as an urgent Orchestrator bug or \`self_dev\`; work already available to the profile proceeds directly, and external/user-owned project work remains \`project_dev\` without admin help. The agents resolve the owner's identity from profile context and durable memory. The owner agent runs in the admin profile with its own memory, integrations, and action policy; it can answer or perform already-authorized owner-scoped work, but the request is never human approval and never transfers admin permissions. If fresh input/approval is required, the owner agent creates an internal Inbox item for the owner. Requests, terminal status, and cross-profile audit events are retained for 90 days; requests are secret-redacted, rate-limited, one-at-a-time per member, and hidden from normal chat lists.
</profiles>

<navigation>
Left sidebar (collapsible to an icon rail). Pages, top to bottom:
- Chat ("/") — the main conversation surface. New chat button; Search (also Cmd/Ctrl-K) is accent-insensitive (matches Romanian text without diacritics) and searches titles + message contents both client-side and server-side. Conversation list shows "Recents" (non-archived); a hover/again-tap Archive toggle flips to the "Archive" view.
- Inbox ("/inbox") — results/notifications from scheduled tasks and monitors. The sidebar item carries a dark-red unread badge (count, or "99+").
- Library ("/library") — everything generated or attached, in tabs.
- Watchlist ("/watchlist") — track financial instruments and products.
- Scheduling ("/scheduling") — create and manage scheduled tasks.
- Smart Monitor ("/monitor") — ongoing, model-owned monitoring.
- Smart Maps ("/maps") — full-screen interactive map.
- Settings ("/settings") — configuration (footer). Admin sees all tabs; member profiles see only the tabs allowed by their profile permissions.

Conversation management (sidebar):
- Auto-naming: a new chat gets a placeholder, then after the first exchange the Conversation Namer agent names it in the user's language (≤~30 chars). It never overwrites a title the user changed manually.
- Archive / Restore / Delete: normal rows can be Archived (hover button on desktop; long-press ~0.5s or right-click on mobile). The Archive view exposes Restore and Delete per row. There is no delete in Recents — archive first, then delete from the Archive view.
- Unread: a conversation is marked unread when an assistant reply finishes while the user isn't looking at it (different page, hidden tab, or a different active conversation). Opening it clears the unread state; that read state syncs live across open devices, and a device that reconnects reconciles the latest server state. A completion push is suppressed when that exact conversation is open and visible on the device, even if an installed macOS PWA reports unreliable focus state, so an answer finishing in front of the user does not also produce a redundant "Chat finished" notification.
- Drafts and per-conversation artifact-panel widths persist locally.
</navigation>

<chat_surface>
Input (the composer):
- Text: Enter sends, Shift+Enter is a newline (on a mobile keyboard Enter inserts a newline — use the send button). On phones the composer stays focused and locally tracks the software keyboard without scrolling the whole document; sending keeps that viewport steady while the new user turn glides to the same near-top anchor used on desktop, with the transcript's virtual tail space preserved for the reply below it. Markdown list markers ("1.", "-", "A.") get a tab-style gap before the item text; Shift+Enter inside a markdown list auto-continues the next bullet/number/letter, and on an empty list item it ends the list (Word-style).
- Secrets: high-confidence API keys, tokens, passwords, webhook/client secrets, private keys, and explicit SECRET_NAME=value assignments are detected while typing. The composer shows the inferred env name before Send. On send, the server saves the value in that profile's private chat-secret vault (0600), also upserts the isolated profile's \`.env.local\` when writable, and replaces the value with a non-secret marker before conversation persistence, model input, request logs, search previews, or sync events. In the user bubble the value is masked immediately — including the optimistic pre-server bubble — with Show/Hide; reveal is same-profile, same-conversation/message checked, request-guarded, no-store, and kept only in that component's local state. Copy message copies a hidden-value label, never the secret. A shared-env member still gets an immediately usable profile-private vault entry even though the inherited admin env file stays read-only.
- Context window: the small ring beside Send shows how full the selected model's context is. Open the status popover, then expand "Context window" for a segmented breakdown of messages, the skill index, active tool schemas, system prompt, memory files/recall, agent roster, attachments, provider/tool-loop state, and free space. Tool schemas and full skill instructions that are discoverable but not loaded appear separately as deferred and do not count against the window. The total comes from the provider when available; category sizes are measured locally and reconciled to that total, while a new/draft conversation is explicitly a local estimate. The same panel keeps last-request input/output/reasoning/cache detail, session totals, and context-compaction history.
- Creative: when the orchestrator agent has a configured Fallback 1 model, the composer shows a Creative toggle (sparkles). While active, each chat turn starts directly on Fallback 1 while keeping the normal primary/fallback list as recovery if that attempt fails. It is a transient composer toggle, not a saved profile model override: it defaults off, does not persist across reloads, and resets when you switch conversations, so it never silently lingers on.
- Attachments: the "+" button, drag-and-drop, or paste. Multiple files. They upload immediately; sending is blocked until every attachment finishes uploading. Click an attachment chip to preview it in-app: a full PDF viewer whose thumbnail rail starts collapsed on phones and open on desktop (password-protected PDFs show an in-viewer unlock prompt; agents read them by passing the user-provided password to Read, or by decrypting a workspace copy with qpdf), image/video lightbox, Excel/CSV as a scrollable multi-sheet grid (cell formatting, column widths, merged cells), PowerPoint as rendered slides, Word (.docx), Markdown (.md) rendered GitHub-style as typeset prose (tables/task lists/code blocks, with a toggle to the raw source), other source/text files syntax-highlighted with line numbers, and SVG rendered as a sanitized image (with a source toggle). Image preview has built-in annotation tools: a select/move tool, pen, highlighter, eraser, shapes (arrow, line, rectangle, ellipse), text, color swatches plus a custom color picker and image eyedropper, brush/text size controls with live px preview on the image, undo/redo, clear, zoom, and download. Both the PDF viewer and the image editor zoom with pinch (touch or trackpad) or Ctrl/Cmd+scroll, anchored on the cursor/fingers, plus toolbar buttons; on phones the image editor's toolbar is a compact two-row layout with the color palette, custom color picker, eyedropper, and secondary actions behind a color dot + ⋮ menu. It opens in Select mode — click a mark to select it, drag to move it, drag the handles to resize shapes, press Delete to remove it, pick a swatch/custom color/eyedropped color to recolor the selection, and drag empty space (or the Hand tool) to pan; dragging never draws until you pick a drawing tool. When opened from a draft composer/Inbox reply, Save re-uploads the annotated PNG, replaces that draft attachment, closes the preview, and returns focus to the message box so the user can add text and send. When opened from the main chat, the image editor also shows a small message input and send button; sending exports the annotated PNG, uploads it as a fresh attachment, and posts it back to the current conversation with the optional typed note. Images opened from Library or non-chat workspace file cards can still be annotated and downloaded without changing the original stored upload. Audio plays inline. Anything not previewable keeps a Download fallback.
- Voice: the Mic button records a voice note. It is uploaded and sent as an AUDIO ATTACHMENT (not transcribed in the browser). A pure voice-note message (no typed text) may get the server audio pre-pass before the main model when needed; if the user also typed text, the whole text+audio message goes straight to the orchestrator to decide what to do. Voice notes land in Library → Audio.
- Live voice mode: the waveform button next to the Mic opens a full-screen real-time spoken conversation (Gemini Live) — the user talks, the assistant answers with voice, and the user can interrupt mid-sentence. It shows live captions, a mute toggle, and an end-call button. The voice agent can control Home Assistant (allowlisted home-control domains only — locks/alarms are always refused from voice), search the web for fresh facts, and hand complex/slow work to a background agent, announcing the result out loud when it finishes. Each session's transcript is saved as a normal conversation in the sidebar; it starts with a "Voice chat HH:MM" fallback using the app-configured timezone, then the Conversation Namer replaces it after the first saved exchange when possible. Enable/disable, voice, live model, and the Home Assistant allowlist live in Settings → Voice (admin).
- Drafts persist per conversation.
- Steering (messages while the agent works): the composer stays live during a streaming turn — the placeholder flips to "Write a follow-up..." and Send never blocks. The message first shows directly above the composer, styled exactly like a normal sent user bubble (it just hasn't joined the transcript yet). When the running engine supports mid-turn steering (Codex), the message is injected INTO the turn in progress: it moves to its exact injection point inside the assistant's response, marked with a "Steered message" label, and the agent adjusts course before saying anything further. If the root is sleeping inside a synchronous sub-agent call, an explicit steer reacquires one global active slot and temporarily wakes it: it can inspect the active synchronous batch, cancel child work made obsolete by the new instruction, do a bounded course correction, or call the delegation manager's sleep action to release that slot and leave the child running; sync remains the default and spontaneous provider activity cannot wake the parent. On engines without live steering (or if the injection is refused / the message has attachments), the message is queued instead and runs automatically as the next turn the moment the current one finishes (one at a time, in order). The Stop button both aborts the current turn AND drops any queued follow-ups. If the app is closed before a queued follow-up runs, the server runs it anyway and the answer is waiting on return.
- Live task list: when the running agent publishes a Todo list, it stays above the composer and updates statuses in place. Lightweight stream-recovery snapshots preserve this list, so periodic background reconciliation does not make it disappear and reappear.
- Update handoff: after a Docker install has migrated to the generation-aware worker, fetching/building leaves the current AI worker open, then the updater starts a second worker on the new image and atomically directs NEW chat, Inbox, scheduled-run-now, model-research, memory-reindex, and generated-App AI requests to it. Already-accepted work stays on its old worker/code until its whole tree finishes; Stop/Steer, active-run lookup, Browser Agent live controls, and chat-sync events keep following the owning generation. The web app can update immediately instead of making every profile wait for one long AI job. Background scheduler/monitor machinery has one explicit owner and pauses only during the overlap, then resumes on the new generation; a brand-new Browser Agent run also waits for that short overlap because both generations share one browser profile, while ordinary model work remains available. A bridge restart or retirement failure resumes the same forward-only handoff rather than sending admission backward. The first upgrade from the older single-worker architecture, single-process installs, CLI updates, restore restarts, and rollbacks to legacy images still use a bounded drain when two compatible generations are impossible. Chat's persisted "Waiting for update" retry remains as a fail-safe for those compatibility windows and infrastructure failures: it preserves stable message ids across reload/tab/app restarts, reattaches instead of duplicating, and Stop clears the pending retry.

Messages and what the user sees:
- Captured credentials render as compact shielded pills with their env name and a Show/Hide button. The raw value is not part of the saved message; the model sees only that the named secret is stored and ready to inject, so it should use the key without asking the user to paste it again.
- Assistant replies interleave "Thinking" reasoning blocks and prose. The Thinking block is collapsible (expand/collapse persists per message), shows a live "Thinking (Ns)" timer while streaming, and contains the agent's reasoning plus a compact disclosure row for every tool call. During a live turn only the newest two tool disclosures stay open; opening another closes the oldest. A finished historical trace first loads its lightweight tool titles/statuses, then fetches a tool's full arguments, result, and streamed output only when that individual row is opened. A tool title always stays above its detail card. The compact live trace is bottom-anchored and clipped rather than scrolled, so a low tool grows upward as one title-plus-detail unit; "Show more" expands the trace in normal page layout with no nested trace scrollbar or programmatic scroll. Expansion is smooth and at most two tool panels stay open. The finalized "Worked for" trace is bottom-anchored so closing it removes content from the top and does not disturb the part of the answer being read below. It auto-expands when there are notable tool calls and stays open while the current browser-agent thread is actively running. On desktop, a starting browser-agent run AUTO-OPENS the right side panel with a browser-optimized remembered width, the live view on top, and Console / Network / Transcript tabs underneath. While the panel hosts a run, its inline block collapses to a "live in side panel" chip; closing it restores the inline view without interrupting the run. The browser panel closes automatically as soon as the run finishes or pauses. A real user-takeover request (an \`ask\`, such as login or confirmation) remains visible as an inline live browser card in chat, outside the finalized "Worked for" disclosure, so it cannot be hidden inside a dropdown; the user can deliberately reopen the side panel for details. Internal browser checkpoints also release the panel and explicitly say no user action is required. Auto-surfacing never focuses the remote page or steals keyboard input — the user clicks inside the live view when ready.
- Sub-agent calls render as agent cards rather than raw delegate tool output. A card says "waiting for global capacity" while the run is waiting for an active-agent slot (work in other conversations or background tasks counts too), then flips to running only after admission; queued work itself consumes no active slot. A direct child launched with root-only \`delegate_async\` is explicitly labeled "async" in its card/workspace metadata. \`delegate_to\` and \`delegate_parallel\` are always synchronous: the child streams its card/workspace while the parent is suspended, and the parent resumes only after the result returns. For genuinely independent overlap, the root can use the separate \`delegate_async\` tool for one or many jobs, continue the declared independent parent work, then collect, efficiently wait once, or cancel through the async delegation manager; one completion wake is armed automatically. Async batch/job/thread state is persisted per profile and caller/thread scope; queued jobs remain durably queued until concurrency admission, live batches register with the durable worker so managed updates drain them before rotation, and an unexpected process death marks unfinished rows lost rather than blindly replaying potentially side-effecting work. Each card shows status, CHILD tool count, output size, and whether the full transcript is saved in the persistent agent thread; top-level tool panels in the same trace are explicitly labeled "Parent agent" so simultaneous parent/child activity remains attributable. Opening the card shows the full child prompt/output/reasoning pane with a Copy-full-output control. The main transcript shows only root Orchestrator's direct children; every nested run, queued or active or finished, appears exclusively in its direct parent's workspace, with deeper generations recursively nested under the selected child rather than duplicated or hidden. When that agent has several sub-agents, their chips switch the nested preview in place instead of replacing the main agent pane. Persona names are made distinct from the parent and siblings, with a display suffix retained defensively for older duplicate-name runs. If a live/tool preview looks clipped, the persisted agent thread remains the source of truth.
- Files the agent produces show up in the message itself, not only as text. A generated image referenced inline (Markdown \`![](…)\`, including by its workspace path) renders as an actual image, click-to-zoom. A link to a workspace file (PDF, Office, code/text, HTML, 3D model, image) or to a stored upload (\`/api/uploads/<id>\` — e.g. Gmail/WhatsApp attachments the agent saved) renders as a compact file card that opens the SAME in-app viewer used for attachment chips — PowerPoint decks convert to slides server-side on open, and HTML under \`files/\` opens as a static rendered preview with scripts blocked plus a source toggle. Mail/newsletter/Gmail-draft HTML that the user needs to inspect before sending belongs in this file-link flow, not as a conversation artifact. Files with no in-app viewer (archives, etc.) stay a one-click link/download.
- Browser-agent queue isolation: only one browser run per profile owns the live browser at a time. While another conversation owns it, a new browser card/panel says "waiting in queue" and mounts neither live view nor diagnostics. Once it acquires its own persisted browser session id, those surfaces target only that exact session and never fall back to another conversation's display.
- Hover a message for the timestamp and a Copy button.

Artifacts (rich, self-contained outputs the agent emits). Each renders inline, in a resizable side panel ("Open artifact"), or full-screen ("/artifact/[id]") depending on the agent's display choice. Newly generated side-panel artifacts auto-open after they are persisted; inline artifacts stay in the chat unless the user expands them, and full-screen artifacts stay as launch cards. If a turn creates or updates an artifact/app card/live preview through tools but the final prose forgets to reference it, chat appends the missing card at the end of the assistant response so the output stays visible after streaming and reload. The panel offers a Preview⇄Code toggle, a version dropdown (history of that artifact), Copy, Download, Open-in-new-tab, and Fullscreen. Types:
- text/markdown, application/vnd.ant.code (highlighted source), text/html (sandboxed live page/app for Orchestrator-native interactive HTML, not mail-client previews), application/vnd.ant.react (live React component), application/vnd.ant.mermaid (diagram), image/svg+xml, text/csv (table), application/json, application/x-latex.
- Explanatory visuals are expected as inline artifacts rather than ASCII line diagrams: Mermaid/SVG/HTML/React for 2D, and rotatable 3D artifacts when spatial/mechanical depth matters. Real CAD/printable/assembly work uses application/vnd.ant.cad; conceptual 3D explainers can use an inline HTML/React WebGL/Three.js surface with orbit/zoom/drag controls.
- application/vnd.ant.map — interactive Google map (pins/routes/areas, multi-day trip tabs); "Open in Smart Maps".
- application/vnd.ant.weather — iOS-style weather card (current, 24h scroll, 10-day, UV/wind/sunrise tiles).
- application/vnd.ant.recipe — recipe card with an interactive servings stepper that live-scales ingredient quantities; lands in Library → Recipes.
- application/vnd.ant.workout — interactive workout session. Start appears near the top of the workout; once active, Finish/Discard appear at the bottom of the workout content instead of as a sticky session band. After Start, the user can tap any pending set in any order; the highlighted row is just the next unfinished suggestion. The working-set timer appears in the bottom bar; Finish stops it and opens a compact editor for actual weight/reps/duration/RPE/notes. For timed movements such as plank, that editor starts from the elapsed timer value, not the programmed target. Save logs the set, starts the rest timer with chimes, and autosaves progress. During rest, the bottom rest bar can start the next set for that same exercise when one remains, otherwise the next unfinished set in workout order, closing the rest event cleanly. Individual sets can be skipped from the row menu; if the user taps Finish workout before completing everything, the remaining sets are confirmed and marked skipped with an optional reason. During an active workout the user can add extra sets or add a new weighted/bodyweight/non-kg resistance exercise from a dialog with full muscle-group coverage including back/pull groups; resistance exercises track their real machine unit (for example Kinesis level) without pretending it is kg. Added exercises scroll into view, join progress, next-set order, summary, and saved history. On phones, workout typing fields get local scroll room and workout dialogs contract above the software keyboard, so the active field and its text remain visible without moving the whole document. Set notes open in a custom workout dialog rather than a browser prompt. Completed/failed/skipped sets remain editable after Finish workout, and changed actuals/RPE/notes re-save the finished session. Finish workout opens a custom feedback dialog with optional session comments and a 1–5 star rating; those fields are saved in the session JSON/markdown and shown in the completion summary. The renderer records set timer duration and rest timer events so later workout-history tools can coach from real timing, not only reps/weight/RPE. The exercise info button expands an inline panel with longer description, alternatives, video, relevant term explanations, and a demo image. Only a model-verified image saved for that stable exercise id is shown; the model manually searches and visually checks first-time media, the renderer does not guess a fuzzy fallback, and images use contained aspect-ratio display without cropping. In-progress sessions autosave to the server keyed by the current artifact and are copied forward when the same sessionId workout is re-emitted, so a started session resumes after a reload, an inbox re-open, or on another device — not just in the same browser. The full-screen surface keeps floating Back and New chat controls available while scrolling: Back follows browser history, New chat exits into a clean conversation, and returning restores the workout's prior scroll position. If the user leaves an active workout before finishing, a global floating workout button follows them around the app with the current rest/set status and returns to the workout surface. The full-screen workout surface requests a screen wake lock while it is open and visible, so supported iPhone browsers do not dim/lock the screen mid-session; it releases automatically when the user leaves the surface or the page is hidden. The full-screen workout surface also has an in-surface AI coach — a docked lateral chat on desktop and a full-screen coach on mobile opened from the floating Coach button. When the workout/map was generated in main chat, the side chat loads that source conversation; inbox, system, handoff, or manually opened surfaces start with a blank new side chat instead. The user can ask it to adjust the session live (swap an exercise, make it harder, add a finisher) or attach a photo (a machine, a form check); when it edits, it updates the workout in place (a targeted patch, or a full re-emit for big changes) so the plan updates live while logged progress is preserved. Finished sessions save a summary and land in Library → Workouts; the first completion also persists the exercise's canonical definition so future generated sessions reuse it and mainly change planned sets, load, reps, and progression.
- application/vnd.ant.app-link — compact launch card for a registered internal app; opens the app's current code version in a new browser tab.
- application/vnd.ant.cad — interactive 3D CAD model viewer (orbit/zoom/pan, grid, wireframe, auto-rotate, size chip) backed by a GLB file the agent generated in the workspace, with download chips for STEP/STL/3MF/source. Produced by the bundled \`cad\` skill (build123d parametric modeling; the \`step-parts\` skill fetches real STEP models of named purchasable parts like servos and screws). The user can print the downloaded STL/3MF/STEP with their own slicer. Standalone .glb/.stl/.3mf files in chat or Library also open in the same 3D viewer.
- application/vnd.ant.question — a structured question card the orchestrator poses via the \`ask_user\` tool when a real decision is genuinely the user's to make and can't be settled from context or a safe default. Carries 1–4 questions on one card; each renders tappable single- or multi-select options (plus an optional free-text "Other" field) that toggle on tap without sending. A single "Send" button (enabled once every question is answered) submits all answers at once — posting them as the user's next chat message to continue the turn — and the card locks to a read-only "Answered" state so it can't be answered twice. Orchestrator-only; it never replaces the confirmation summary required for money/send/account actions.
- application/vnd.ant.dev-preview — a live "mini-browser" for temporary Orchestrator self-development previews (and rare explicit diagnostic previews). The helper runs a loopback dev server and reverse-proxies it through the app at \`/dev-preview/<run-id>/\`; this artifact embeds that live preview in an iframe (URL bar, reload, open-in-new-tab) and AUTO-OPENS the side panel so the user can inspect the running Orchestrator change without host localhost access. Preview metadata carries \`publicUrl\` and a LAN-accessible \`lanUrl\` when available; agents should give those plain links too, never only \`localhost\`. Edits are picked up with the reload control (the proxy doesn't carry Next's HMR socket). New user-owned websites/apps should not normally use this artifact; durable static apps publish under \`/published-apps/<slug>/\`.
Recipe/map/workout artifacts also appear automatically in the matching Library tab; everything else (markdown, code, HTML/React pages, SVG, CSV, JSON, diagrams) lands in Library → Artifacts. Static web projects published through \`project_dev\` are not conversation artifacts, but their durable profile-scoped \`/published-apps/<slug>/\` entries appear in Library → Artifacts → Webpages.
Internal apps: the agent can build reusable mini-apps — any self-contained interactive tool (calculators, planners, trackers, generators, dashboards, configurators, games, …) — as html/react artifacts registered under a stable slug, with a persistent per-app JSON data store shared by the running app (window.AppHost bridge) and the agent's AppData tools — so the user can add data or request changes from any later conversation. Apps can also call the active Orchestrator model through AppHost.ai with an app-authored prompt, optional structured JSON output, and common photo/PDF/text/data inputs (for example a calorie tracker that estimates a meal from a photo). The call is tool-free and exposes no provider key, browser, or persistent model memory; uploaded bytes are transient, while useful results can be saved in the app's JSON document. External/public apps need an explicitly designed own backend/deployment and cannot reuse the private AppHost/model session. Saved apps sit pinned at the top of Library → Artifacts.
Full web projects: when the user asks for a complete site/app/project rather than a single self-contained artifact, the agent uses the standalone project-development flow (separate from Orchestrator self-development): it prepares an isolated repo under \`.orchestrator/project-runs/<run-id>/repo\`, delegates coding there, verifies a real build, and for production-ready static outputs (Vite quiz/game/dashboard/landing page, static assets, exported Next.js) runs \`project-run:run publish-static\`. That builds with \`PUBLISHED_BASE_PATH=/published-apps/<slug>\`, copies the static output into the active profile workspace under \`published-apps/<slug>/\`, returns stable Public/LAN URLs served by the same Orchestrator container/reverse proxy, lists the result in Library → Artifacts → Webpages, and tries to create a Tailscale Funnel scoped only to \`/published-apps/<slug>\`. When the host bridge and Tailscale are ready, the result includes \`tailscaleFunnelUrl\`; agents should give the user both \`lanUrl\` and \`tailscaleFunnelUrl\` (plus \`publicUrl\` if configured), and say why when the Funnel URL is unavailable. The share path serves only that static app without requiring an Orchestrator profile cookie; the rest of Orchestrator remains profile-gated. Share records are profile-scoped even when they live in the shared state file, so one profile's slug does not mark another profile's same slug public. These published apps persist across container restarts because they live in the mounted workspace. They run under a strict same-origin CSP that allows WebAssembly, Web Workers, and \`fetch\` of the app's OWN vendored assets (so client-side wasm/OCR/data libraries like tesseract.js work when their full asset set is vendored same-origin) but blocks cross-origin/CDN network, WebSockets, and the Orchestrator API; host nginx/vhost/Docker changes are fallback deploy work for backend/SSR/custom-service cases and require explicit approval. Interactive apps do NOT belong under \`/files\` because that route intentionally blocks scripts. Orchestrator self-development is reserved for changing this app itself.
Project-development routing is based on which product/codebase changes, not on complexity or hosting. A user-owned app remains \`project_dev\` when it grows a backend, database, authentication, app-internal admin roles, APIs, SSR, cron, Docker, or a production deployment; the Orchestrator admin profile and \`self_dev\` are only for changing Orchestrator itself. Member profiles do not see the self-development subsystem in their normal menu; if they nevertheless request it for an external product and it is refused, the refusal directs the agent back to \`project_dev\` instead of treating admin access as a blocker. Project preparation now selects \`--delivery static\` for browser-only output or \`--delivery server\` for full-stack/server-backed output. Static delivery uses \`publish-static\`; server delivery gets its own backend/auth/database and reproducible runtime, persistence, migration, backup, security, deployment, cutover, and rollback contract, while build/test work continues safely in the isolated repo and exact host/provider changes wait for separate approval.
The strict-schema types (map, weather, recipe, workout, cad, question) are validated before any surface stores them — live chat, scheduled runs, microscript notifications, and inline Inbox replies alike; if a body fails validation, the same generating/owning agent runtime gets the exact error and repairs the JSON in-place before the message is delivered, so the corrected card appears without the user having to ask for a redo (only a repair that still fails after retries surfaces an error notice). If a card briefly shows "could not be displayed" after reopening the app, the client refetches it automatically — that notice only sticks for content that genuinely failed validation.
</chat_surface>

<inbox_surface>
A mail-style client for scheduled-run results, monitor alerts, replies, and handoffs.
- What creates an item: the agent (a scheduled task or a monitor wake) calls the notify_inbox tool with a title, a user-facing markdown body, and optional quick-reply actions. Ordinary chat does NOT create Inbox items. Items are system-owned conversations kept separate from user chats.
- List: search; folder chips Inbox / Unread / Read / Scheduled (items tied to a scheduled task); grouped Today / Yesterday / Earlier. An item re-marks unread when a new reply arrives.
- Opening an item marks it read. Header actions: "Open in chat" forks the thread into a normal chat; Delete.
- Quick-reply action buttons under an assistant message: reply-type actions continue the thread inline (handled by the Inbox agent); "direct" actions run a whitelisted housekeeping tool server-side WITHOUT invoking a model (e.g. Gmail mark-read/archive, WhatsApp mark-read, and sending an agent-composed Gmail draft via gmail.send_draft). Reply proposals: for mail that clearly awaits the user's reply, the agent can draft a real Gmail draft and surface it as an Inbox item quoting the full draft text, with a one-tap "Send reply" button (the tap is the send approval — nothing sends without it) plus a rework option that revises the draft conversationally. Which proposals get sent, reworked, or ignored feeds the agent's learning about when to propose at all. A free-text composer (with attachments) replies inline too.
- Push notifications: Profile menu → Notifications ("/profile/notifications") is the normal per-profile control surface; the in-Inbox bell is a quick enable button. A browser/device endpoint belongs to one profile at a time; enabling it under a new profile removes that endpoint from other profiles so pushes do not cross profiles.
</inbox_surface>

<library_surface>
One hub for "everything you've generated or attached." Tabs are ordered Artifacts, Workouts, Recipes, Maps, Places, Media, Audio, Files. What fills each:
- Artifacts — registered internal apps (pinned "Apps" section on top, with delete), published static webpages/apps from \`/published-apps/<slug>/\` (the "Webpages" section), plus the latest version of every other conversation artifact (markdown, code, HTML/React, SVG, CSV, JSON, diagrams), with search and per-type filter chips. App code artifacts are hidden from the generic artifact grid once they have an App card, so the same app does not appear twice. App cards open "/artifact/[id]" in a new browser tab; Webpage cards open the durable published URL and include a Share button that creates/copies a public outside-LAN link for that profile's page (using the configured public HTTPS origin when available, otherwise a scoped Tailscale Funnel). Other artifact cards open the artifact route in the current tab. Workout/recipe/map/weather types are excluded because they have their own homes; transient question cards and app-link chat chrome are excluded too.
- Workouts / Recipes / Maps — populated automatically from the matching chat artifacts. The Workouts tab only appears for profiles with the Workouts surface enabled; if Workouts is disabled, Library deep links to that tab fall back to the first allowed tab (normally Artifacts). When visible, Workouts is a history dashboard built from saved sessions: a training calendar (a GitHub-style heatmap of training days over the last ~16 weeks plus a week-streak, this-week, and last-30-day count), progress cards (recent sessions, volume trend, PRs), a weekly muscle-balance breakdown (completed sets per muscle group over a 7- or 30-day window, counting each muscle a compound lift targets), a recent-session list where each row also surfaces average rest time and skipped-rest count, per-exercise PR/history trends, and a Body metrics card where the user can log height, weight, body fat %, and muscle % (percentages of bodyweight) and see a body-weight trend sparkline; IMC/BMI is calculated from the latest height+weight. Clicking an artifact opens the full interactive renderer ("/artifact/[id]" or "/maps/[id]").
- Places — the optional Location Intelligence journal (Home Assistant location webhooks → a local daily journal). Off until the user opts in.
- Media (images+videos) / Audio (voice notes, music) / Files (PDFs, Office docs, code, other) — populated from two sources: chat/inbox attachments AND files the agent writes into allowlisted workspace output dirs. A file appears in the Library Files tab only if it lives in one of: files/, browser-downloads/, gmail-attachments/, artifacts/ (or is an upload). Standard workspace files (USER.md, MEMORY.md, runbooks, config) are deliberately NOT listed here. Workspace files under files/ also have profile-gated direct links at /files/<path-inside-files>; HTML opened through those direct links renders there with scripts blocked. Static web apps published through project_dev live under workspace published-apps/ and are served from /published-apps/<slug>/ instead of the Files tab, but they are listed in Library → Artifacts → Webpages; their Webpage Share button can make the same path public through the configured HTTPS origin or a scoped Tailscale Funnel without exposing other app pages. Chat file cards and downloads use the /api/workspace/files endpoint; when that endpoint receives a workspace directory path, it downloads a zip of the directory instead of showing a file-preview card. → This is why create_backup saves into files/: so the archive shows in Library → Files.
- Cross-tab actions on Media/Audio/Files: search, a selection mode for bulk Download / Share / Delete, a media lightbox, and "View in chat" to jump to the source message. In the Files tab, clicking a file name (or its Eye button) opens the same in-app viewer used in chat — PDFs, Excel/CSV, PowerPoint, Word, HTML, and code/text render in-app; the rest fall back to Open-in-new-tab / Download. For workspace HTML under files/, Open-in-new-tab uses the /files/<path> static preview route instead of the download API. Deleting removes the upload or the workspace file; standard workspace files can't be deleted here.
</library_surface>

<settings>
Ten possible tabs (Models, Integrations, Voice, Files, Remote Access, Logs, Usage, Notifications, Profiles, Updates). Voice (admin-only) holds the live voice mode switch, spoken voice picker, live model selection (Automatic tracks Google's newest live-capable Flash), and the Home Assistant voice allowlist. The light/dark Theme toggle is in the Settings header, top-right. The active tab is remembered. Legacy links to \`?tab=auth\` redirect to Integrations. Admin sees every tab. Member profiles see basic Settings tabs (Integrations, Files, Usage, Notifications), plus Models when "Allow model changes" is enabled; Remote Access, Logs, Profiles, and Updates are admin-only. For members, Files is read-only unless the "Settings files" permission is enabled.

<settings_profiles>
Admin profile and access management.
- Profiles list: create profiles, edit name/color/role/password, deactivate/restore non-admin profiles, permanently delete a deactivated profile only after typing its exact name, and inspect recent profile audit events (creation, sign-ins, permission changes, deletes). Deactivation blocks sign-in while preserving profile data for restore; permanent delete can also remove that profile's local workspace/private state.
- Access matrix: per profile, choose visible app surfaces, tool classes (web, read/write files, shell, delegation, skills, scheduling, monitoring, microscripts, backups, updates, "Allow model changes", editable Settings files), personal integration access (none/read/write/setup), shared integration connections, and "Use admin environment". That environment toggle is saved immediately: when on, the member reads the complete admin/process/project env (provider keys, app/public/LAN/SSH URLs, OAuth client configuration and redirect URIs, and other runtime settings), never its own \`.env.local\`; the shared Env file is visible redacted/read-only and member env/config writes are rejected. Turning it off immediately restores the member's isolated env behavior, including any older file that was previously ignored. Watchlist is a local per-profile surface/subsystem, not an external integration. New member profiles default to the main personal workflow: chat/inbox/library/watchlist/Smart Monitor/maps/workouts/settings plus Scheduling, file read/write, browser agent, delegation, web, memory, skills, monitoring, microscripts, and shell are enabled. Member defaults also allow self-service setup for their own Gmail, Google Calendar, Google Workspace, WhatsApp, Home Assistant, and Google Maps credentials/sessions; shared-env members reuse the admin's app credentials while their OAuth tokens/sessions remain profile-specific. Weather stays read-capable through keyless Open-Meteo unless Maps/Google Weather keys are configured. Admin environment sharing is on by default; backups, updates, model changes, and editable settings files stay off.
- Integration access model: Settings → Profiles separates "Personal integrations" from "Shared connections". Personal integrations decide whether the profile may connect/configure/use its own account, token, session, or key. Shared connections let admin grant a profile access to another profile's existing Gmail, Google Calendar, Google Workspace, WhatsApp, or Home Assistant connection. Admin can enable personal setup only, shared access only, or both at the same time. Shared OAuth/token/session access never copies secrets into the member profile; calls run against the owner profile's stored connection and respect the grant's read/write/manage level. Key-based Maps/Weather and shared Google OAuth app credentials use "Use admin environment" plus the profile's personal integration permission; the connected account token remains profile-specific.
- Google account connections: Gmail, Google Calendar, and Google Workspace each support multiple locally stored OAuth account connections per profile. Settings → Integrations shows the available accounts on each Google card and lets the active profile choose its default account for that service; connecting another Google account adds/updates that account under the active profile instead of overwriting the first one. Legacy single-token installs are migrated into that same profile's connection on first status check without deleting the legacy token file. Admin can also grant these connections to other profiles from Settings → Profiles.
- WhatsApp and Home Assistant sharing: a member can connect their own WhatsApp/Home Assistant in Settings → Integrations under their profile context, or admin can grant that member access to another profile's connected WhatsApp/Home Assistant from Settings → Profiles. WhatsApp Connect/Disconnect always apply to the active profile's own Linked Devices session; ordinary WhatsApp operations use the selected accessible connection, which may be own or shared. Home Assistant shared calls use the owner profile's stored token, action policy, and audit files.
- Remote MCP servers: Settings → Integrations → Remote MCP servers is profile-scoped. It stores remote Streamable HTTP MCP endpoint config and OAuth tokens locally in that profile's private state. The app supports browser OAuth for MCP servers and no-auth endpoints for trusted/local testing; it does not run arbitrary local stdio MCP server commands from Settings.
- Sharing model: profiles never share DB/browser state or ordinary workspace files. "Use admin environment" is the explicit env-only exception; integration tokens/sessions remain profile-specific unless an explicit shared connection grant is enabled.
- Logs/user visibility: Logs is admin-only and aggregates model request logs across profiles; rows show the profile that produced the request. The Profiles tab shows profile/session/permission audit events.
</settings_profiles>

<settings_models>
Per-agent model configuration plus the model registry and semantic-memory setup.
- For each agent: pick the Model, the Thinking level, model-specific Features, and up to two ordered Fallback models. Agents are listed in a reorderable sidebar (drag to reorder), with a separate pinned "System" group for agents that run automatically. Media-agent pickers show only models of the matching kind (image/video/speech/music), preventing a text model from being saved on a media agent. The retired saved image-agent id \`google:gemini-3.1-flash-image\` is interpreted as the new \`codex:imagegen\` default; choosing the current Google preview or OpenAI image model explicitly remains supported.
- Fallback models are tried automatically on provider availability failures such as rate limits, quota/capacity/overload, expired or revoked-refresh-token sessions, invalid provider requests, or 401/429/503-style errors, as long as the failed attempt has not already emitted assistant prose. The same model is retried up to three times before moving to the next configured fallback. If the model fails after tool activity but before a final answer, retries/fallbacks still get a chance and the next attempt receives a bounded recovery transcript of the already completed tool calls, with explicit instructions not to repeat successful side-effecting work. If visible answer text already streamed, the turn is kept as that provider's error instead of silently restarting. The chat composer's Creative toggle is a shortcut for the orchestrator's Fallback 1: it starts that turn with Fallback 1 but does not rewrite the saved model settings.
- Thinking level is a PER-MODEL capability surfaced per-agent: Off / Low / Med / High / XHigh / Max / Ultra (when the provider offers it), only shown for models that support adjustable thinking, and it auto-normalizes when you switch to a model that doesn't support the current level. It controls the reasoning effort/budget sent to the model — not a global toggle.
- Override resolution: per-agent override → that agent's default → the global default. The right panel labels which is active. For profiles without "Allow model changes", agent model settings and Browser Agent model slots follow the admin-controlled shared defaults. When admin changes an agent override or Browser Agent model slot, it propagates to profiles that do not have self-service model changes enabled. A member profile with "Allow model changes" can choose its own orchestrator/agent/browser-agent models for that profile only; it cannot refresh/research/curate/archive the global model registry.
- Model picker: search across name/provider; Favorites (star, reorderable) at top in the normal list; provider sections show up to four models by default and expose Show more / Show less when more are available. Search results are also grouped by provider with the same four-row preview, while each row still shows provider/source. Archive/Unarchive and Refresh are admin-only global registry actions.
- Top bar "Refresh models" auto-discovers new models from each configured provider. For Claude Code it asks the installed CLI which \`--model\` aliases it currently documents, resolves each alias to the concrete model id the CLI reports, relabels existing picker entries to match (unarchiving ones whose underlying model changed), and adds picker entries for brand-new model families the CLI gained. For Codex CLI it queries the account-aware app-server \`model/list\` catalog and imports every visible model plus its selectable reasoning levels, so newly enabled model families appear without a seed-file update. Keeping both CLIs updated (Settings → Updates → CLI tools) is therefore what brings their newest available models into the picker. Google-discovered models still need research to be "complete"; OpenRouter models use OpenRouter's model API for context window and pricing, so they normally arrive complete without a metadata research run. OpenRouter runtime requests also ask OpenRouter to route a chosen model through the lowest-price upstream provider available for that model. LM Studio is a local/LAN OpenAI-compatible provider: connect it from Settings → Models → Local model runtimes → LM Studio or set \`LM_STUDIO_BASE_URL\` in Settings → Files → .env.local (for example \`http://<Mac LAN IP>:1234/v1\`), start LM Studio's local server with network access if Orchestrator is on another machine, then Refresh models to load the currently available local models. Native LM Studio v1 metadata fills max context, loaded context, reasoning levels, loaded-instance state, quantization/format/size, and $0 token pricing; a per-model "Context length" option controls the context requested when Orchestrator auto-loads the model and defaults to 100k tokens, clamped down to the model's max context when smaller. Optional \`LM_STUDIO_API_KEY\` is sent as a bearer token if that server requires one. Before each LM Studio chat request, Orchestrator tries \`/api/v1/models\`: if native model management is available it serializes load operations per server, unloads other loaded LLM instances by default, loads the selected model with the requested context length, and then calls the OpenAI-compatible Chat Completions endpoint so Orchestrator function tools keep working. Set \`LM_STUDIO_AUTO_UNLOAD=false\` to leave other loaded LM Studio models alone. LM Studio has no provider-side web search/attachments/thinking-output streaming in Orchestrator today; thinking levels are stored from LM Studio metadata for model selection, while the runtime uses Chat Completions for custom tool support.
- "Model metadata" card: a collapsible section showing how many active models have complete vs incomplete metadata. "Review & research (N)" opens a review panel FIRST (it never auto-starts a run) — the left list shows every active model sorted incomplete-first with its missing fields, the right pane shows the selected model's current metadata; an explicit "Start research (N)" button then runs the researcher agent to fill pricing/context/thinking for the incomplete models from official docs (streamed live, stoppable), and each model has its own "Re-research" action. Closing the panel (X) collapses it straight back to the summary row with no leftover bar; "Clear" wipes the saved run log. Fully responsive (the controls and the list/detail split stack on narrow screens).
- Local model runtimes (admin-only): LM Studio, Claude Code, and Codex CLI live in Settings → Models. LM Studio lets the admin enter a server URL and optional API key, Ping it, Auto-detect & Connect by scanning localhost, \`host.docker.internal\`, common home LAN \`/24\` ranges, and detected private LAN ranges on port 1234, and Forget the saved config. Connect first verifies the server, saves \`LM_STUDIO_BASE_URL\` / optional \`LM_STUDIO_API_KEY\`, refreshes the LM Studio model list, and the card polls status about every 10 seconds so stopping the LM Studio server shows as Offline. Claude Code and Codex CLI each show install state, login state, Log in / Reconnect / Log out, Restart, and the binary path. Codex logout clears both the isolated runtime credential and the source credential that seeds it before the terminal can be closed, then drops cached login truth. If both Codex app-server and the fallback usage endpoint reject the same credentials after refresh, Orchestrator also invalidates those dead copies automatically so Models no longer says Logged in and a configured model fallback becomes eligible. The Image Generator defaults to the virtual Codex ImageGen model: it starts a locked-down app-server image turn, verifies the signed-in account exposes image generation, accepts local reference images, collects the generated file, and charges Codex/ChatGPT plan usage rather than OPENAI_API_KEY; direct OpenAI API and Google image models remain explicit alternatives. Claude Code also offers "Use long-lived token" (mints a non-expiring API token via \`claude setup-token\` — recommended for headless installs since OAuth refresh can drop after a few days) and surfaces an expiry/Reconnect warning when its OAuth session is about to lapse. This is how the orchestrator delegates code work when using a CLI; no API key needed once logged in. Native CLI skills/plugins are intentionally not exposed to Orchestrator agents; specialized workflows come through Orchestrator-owned tools/skills instead of Claude Code/Codex marketplace/plugin state.
- Browser agent is special: it always uses Patchright, so Settings expose a light model plus an optional pro model for hard blockers, restricted to Google/Gemini or Codex CLI text models. Normal runs use the profile-scoped persistent cookie jar; Orchestrator can instead launch a fresh delegated run in incognito mode, which creates a temporary isolated profile. That mode is selected by Orchestrator before the browser_agent starts — the browser agent cannot turn a persistent managed session into incognito through browser UI. If Chromium dies, the controller discards stale handles and relaunches the same persistent profile on the next action. The controller is vision/coordinate-first and can operate page content, popups, canvas, browser chrome, and native prompts; bounded DOM assistance can inspect a coordinate or inventory controls across same/cross-origin frames and open shadow roots, then target fresh refs for click/type/key/hover/scroll/clear, native selects, and checkbox state. Clicks support left/middle/right buttons and keyboard modifiers, while targeted waits can observe URL, text, ref state, or page load instead of sleeping blindly. Page content is treated as untrusted evidence and cannot change the delegated goal or permissions. The agent can inventory page images/media/fonts/stylesheets/SVGs and save one selected media resource to managed downloads, but cannot bulk-scrape assets or run arbitrary page code/CDP. Viewport backends also support mobile/tablet/desktop presets and dark-mode emulation. The exact browser action surface shown to Orchestrator and accepted by the browser-model schema comes from one runtime manifest, preventing delegation instructions from drifting away from real tools. Every model frame includes semantic document-scroll state (percentage, visible range, remaining content, and top/bottom flags); after targeted wheel/End input, the action result names the document or internal panel that actually moved and reports that target's own position. Full-display captures use real DOM metrics when available and explicitly report scroll as unknown otherwise, never as a fabricated zero. Browser evidence screenshots/videos attach inline; diagnostics feed the Console/Network tabs. The live view stays interactive at all times, with a separate scaled agent-pointer overlay plus clipboard Copy/Paste sync.
- Memory recall card (bottom): enable semantic memory, choose the embedding model + dimensions (Google/Gemini, reuses the existing Gemini key — no separate billing) and a recall threshold; Rebuild index after switching models. Powers the automatic per-turn recall and the memory_search tool. The test search shows both raw score distribution and an "automatic recall preview" that applies the real threshold, context exclusions, deduping, and coverage gate.
</settings_models>

<settings_integrations>
Connect external services and manage Orchestrator-owned workflow skills. Member profiles can use this tab for self-service personal integrations when their Personal integration permission is Manage; setup/config/connect/disconnect controls appear for integrations where that profile has setup-level access, and admin can still lower any profile's personal access to read/write/none while separately granting shared connections from Settings → Profiles. A "Recheck" button refreshes all statuses. The connectable services (each a card with live status):
- Gmail — OAuth (popup). Search/read/send/draft, labels, archive/trash, attachments. Shows the selected account, available local accounts, scopes, token expiry, and a paste-client-ID/secret config form if the OAuth client isn't set.
- WhatsApp — local WhatsApp companion session: Connect shows a QR code to scan from Linked Devices. The default provider is Baileys (WebSocket-based, no local browser); \`WHATSAPP_PROVIDER=wwebjs\` switches back to the legacy browser-backed provider, and \`WHATSAPP_PROVIDER=disabled\` is the kill switch (it stops any cached active WhatsApp runtime for that profile and prevents new operations). Mode is "reads plus confirmed writes" (sending/media/delete-for-everyone need explicit confirmation). Read tools include recent chat/search plus older-message/media lookup inside a specific chat; with Baileys these read from a persistent local message store (SQLite next to the session auth state) that survives app restarts and deploys, has no fixed chat cap, requests the phone's full history at QR-pairing time, and keeps filling as messages arrive — it is wiped together with the session on Disconnect and, like the live session, is excluded from backups. Reading from the store is passive (no read receipts; blue ticks only happen via the explicit mark-read tool). The legacy provider can progressively load older Web history instead. Operational WhatsApp calls from tools and Smart Monitor checks are serialized and lightly paced, including batch mark/delete loops, so one model turn or background tick cannot hammer the single local companion session. A stored, resumable Baileys session resumes automatically: status checks kick a background resume after a restart, and transient connection drops auto-reconnect with capped exponential backoff (auth rejection still requires a new QR, and a takeover by another WhatsApp Web session deliberately does not auto-reconnect). A stored Baileys session is shown as resumable only when its paired account identity is present, while partial/corrupt local creds show as reconnect-required. Connect clears incomplete/auth-failed Baileys local auth state before showing a fresh QR.
- Google Calendar — OAuth. Events, free/busy, availability, daily briefs, meeting prep, group-slot ranking, focus-time proposals, create/update/move/delete, and RSVP. Calendar operating workflows load with the integration; writes still require confirmation. Supports multiple local account connections with a default-account selector.
- Google Workspace — OAuth (Drive token for Drive + Docs/Sheets/Slides + Contacts). Supports multiple local account connections with a default-account selector.
- Home Assistant — save URL + long-lived token (verified on save). The card shows the active connection for the current profile (own or shared, owner, access level). An action-mode toggle allows direct control of lights/covers/climate/notify while confirming other domains.
- Maps & Weather — one Google Maps Platform API key powers Smart Maps, Geocoding, Places, Routes, and optional Google Weather/Air-Quality/Pollen; without it weather falls back to keyless Open-Meteo. Accepts a pasted .env or a typed key + Vector Map ID; includes a setup tutorial with deep links to enable each Google API.
- Remote MCP servers — custom Streamable HTTP MCP endpoints. The card lets admin save a label/URL/auth mode, start browser OAuth for OAuth-based MCP servers, disconnect local tokens, remove a server, and see tool count / recent tool names. Agents use the generic MCP tools: configure, start OAuth, list tools, then call a selected remote MCP tool through a confirmation-guarded wrapper.
- Location Intelligence — read-only status of the optional local location journal; a button hands a setup prompt to chat. Off until configured.
- Custom Skills — lists global, bundled, and legacy profile workflow skills, shows which entry is active when ids collide, and lets admins create/edit/delete global custom SKILL.md bundles. Add skill supports an outcome-first starter with goal, success criteria, constraints, validation, output, and stop rules, plus pasted/uploaded SKILL.md and HTTPS SKILL.md URL import; GitHub blob URLs are converted to raw automatically. New, imported, and edited custom skills are rejected unless they have supported YAML metadata, a non-empty instruction body, and a compact instruction file (long detail belongs in referenced files); the generated starter itself uses portable metadata. The detail pane renders a Markdown preview by default and exposes Edit for writable global custom skills. Custom skills are shared app state and admin-managed; bundled repository skills are read-only. Custom skills are global-only, and any legacy profile-scoped skill is auto-promoted to the shared global root on boot (skipped only when a global skill already owns that id), so entries no longer linger profile-bound.
For OAuth on a remote/headless host where Google must redirect to localhost: the runtime context provides an SSH tunnel command (ssh -N -L ...) and you open http://localhost:PORT/settings to finish the consent. Keep the tunnel up until status reads Connected.
</settings_integrations>

<settings_remote_access>
How the user reaches Orchestrator and which endpoints (if any) are public. Three sections:
- On your network: the detected LAN URLs (http://<lan-ip>:<port>) — the fastest path. Guidance is domain→LAN primary: point your own domain at a LAN IP for HTTPS at home, and use Tailscale's VPN to reach that same address when away (faster than routing UI traffic over the internet).
- HTTPS / public address: whether a public HTTPS URL is configured (ORCHESTRATOR_PUBLIC_URL) or the full UI is reachable through Tailscale Funnel. HTTPS is required for Google/Gmail sign-in and browser notifications. The panel offers three setup modes. DuckDNS is the automatic path: domain + token + optional email provisions a Let's Encrypt cert + nginx reverse proxy on the host through the bridge (needs root; best-effort). If the host bridge is not connected, the DuckDNS mode explains that automatic setup is unavailable and shows a copyable manual \`bash scripts/install.sh setup-https\` command with the required DuckDNS environment variables. Own domain is the manual custom-domain path: the user enters \`https://orchestrator.example.com\`, Orchestrator validates that the public DNS name reaches \`/api/ping\`, then shows the exact \`ORCHESTRATOR_PUBLIC_URL\` and \`BROWSER_AGENT_VNC_WS_PUBLIC_URL\` lines to add to the host/project env; docs/custom-domain.md has the nginx/TLS examples. Tailscale Funnel is the quick no-DNS public URL: on Docker installs with Tailscale signed in, it toggles a root Funnel for the full Orchestrator UI at \`https://<node>.ts.net/\`; this exposes the app surface to the public internet and is separate from the scoped webhook Funnel.
- Tailscale Funnel: the Remote Access page has two separate Funnel uses. In HTTPS / public address, "Tailscale Funnel" publishes the full Orchestrator UI at the node's \`.ts.net\` URL and requires explicit user confirmation. In Inbound webhooks, a one-click toggle publishes ONLY \`/api/webhooks\` to the internet via a scoped Tailscale Funnel path (the rest of the app stays private) so external services can send events; every webhook still needs its signed secret. Enabling/disabling runs on the host via the update bridge and needs the tailnet Funnel node attribute. The resulting \`https://<node>.ts.net/api/webhooks\` URL is shown to copy. The same host bridge is also used by \`project-run:run publish-static\` and by Library → Artifacts → Webpages share buttons when no configured public HTTPS origin exists; scoped public links for generated static apps live at \`/published-apps/<slug>\`, serve only that app path, and do not expose the Orchestrator UI. If Tailscale isn't installed, the panel offers a best-effort one-click install (with a copy-paste command fallback since it needs root) and then sign-in guidance (\`sudo tailscale up\`, interactive browser auth); autodetect picks it up on Refresh.
- You (the agent) can also DO this, not just point at the tab: remote_access_status reads the same picture, including whether the full-UI Funnel is on; remote_access_enable_webhook_funnel / _disable_ toggles the public /api/webhooks funnel (an outward-facing change — confirm with the user first); remote_access_install_tailscale runs the best-effort install; remote_access_setup_https provisions DuckDNS HTTPS (domain+token). Pair these with the webhook_* tools (create the signed endpoint, then expose it) to fully wire an inbound webhook end to end. Full-UI Funnel is controlled from Settings for now because it exposes the whole app.
</settings_remote_access>

<settings_notifications>
Web Push status and troubleshooting for every device. The same panel is available to every signed-in profile from Profile menu → Notifications and from that profile's Settings → Notifications.
- "This device" card: live browser permission + subscription state (Enabled / Not enabled / Blocked / Unsupported / Error), with Enable, Send test notification, Reset subscription (unsubscribes, deletes the server record, re-subscribes with a fresh endpoint), and Re-check buttons. Blocked/unsupported states show platform-specific guidance (HTTPS required, iOS needs the Home-Screen PWA, browser site settings).
- "Registered devices" list: every push subscription on the server (browser + OS parsed from the user agent, push service, added/last-sync times, "This device" badge), each with a per-device Test send and a Remove button. A test reports whether the push service accepted the message — if accepted but nothing appears on screen, the block is on the device, not the server. Expired endpoints are cleaned up automatically when the push service rejects them.
</settings_notifications>

<settings_files>
Browse the active profile's agent workspace files. Admins and profiles with "Settings files" can edit their own files; other member profiles see the tab read-only. When "Use admin environment" is enabled, Env always shows the admin environment as inherited/read-only with secrets redacted, even if an older member \`.env.local\` still exists on disk; that older file is ignored until sharing is disabled. Categories: Onboarding, Knowledge & memory, Behavior, System. Files:
- USER.md — stable user facts, preferences, constraints, accounts, places, people.
- MEMORY.md — permanent consolidated durable memory; the always-loaded "hot" tier, kept lean by the nightly reflection.
- MEMORY_ARCHIVE.md — "cold" long-term memory: durable facts the reflection demotes out of MEMORY.md when rarely needed. NOT loaded into the prompt every turn, but indexed for semantic recall, so it still surfaces when relevant (lossless demotion).
- Daily memory — a FOLDER (MEMORY_DAY/), one note per app-configured local day; the working-memory ledger. Rendered as a collapsible folder with a date search box when there are many days.
- PLAYBOOKS.md — reusable distilled procedures.
- AGENT_NEEDS.md — backlog of missing capabilities / failed tools / blockers.
- MONITORS.md — monitoring preferences + the active Smart Monitor watch ids. Smart Monitor/Microscript wakes receive a bounded all-entry view plus the exact runtime watch records in their wake packet; the plain chat agent reads it on demand / via recall instead of carrying it every turn.
- BOOT.md / ONBOARDING.md — first-run onboarding only (disappear once onboarding is done). A fresh install first runs a one-time setup wizard at /onboarding (profile → pick each agent's model, with the orchestrator a forced choice → optional service keys → Remote Access/HTTPS → integrations) — desktop-only (mobile shows a "finish on a computer" screen), it ends in a live boot conversation. Established installs are never shown it; ORCHESTRATOR_FORCE_ONBOARDING=1 re-runs it for testing.
- config.json — read-only here ("Edited from the Models tab"); stores app-level defaults including userName, assistantName, and timezone.
- .env.local — secrets and runtime configuration, including provider keys, app/public/LAN/SSH URLs, and OAuth client/redirect settings. An isolated profile owns this file; a shared-env member uses the admin file read-only and cannot change it through Settings, SetEnv, onboarding, or integration config endpoints. Uses EXPLICIT save (never autosaves), values redacted on read, stored with 0600 perms. Credentials pasted in chat are additionally kept in a per-profile private vault and are auto-upserted here when this file is writable. Agents discover configured names with ListEnvVars and pass selected names to Bash via env_keys; the runtime injects only those values and redacts them from tool args/results/output instead of revealing them to the model. Direct \`.env\` access from the managed Bash tool is blocked.
Markdown files autosave ~0.7s after you stop typing. JSON files use a structured tree editor (typed inputs), and invalid JSON blocks saving. Integration runbook files exist (INTEGRATIONS/<id>.md) but are hidden from this list. You (the agent) can edit the markdown memory/behavior files directly with your file tools; config.json is owned by the Models tab.
</settings_files>

<settings_logs>
Every AI request (model call) with full recent detail. Admin sees an aggregate across all profiles, with a Profile column. Filter by search (error/id), time range (1h / 24h / 7d / 30d / All), status (OK / Error / Aborted / Streaming), agent, and provider. A "Live" tail streams new requests. Expanding a recent row shows the same compact per-tool dropdown transcript as chat, a token breakdown (input / output / thinking / cached / tool use / total), request metadata (profile, provider, thinking level, stateful vs stateless mode, tool-call count), and an expandable "Exact model input" section — the full payload sent to the provider for that turn. Tool titles/status arrive first; opening one lazy-loads its persisted arguments, retained result, streamed output, and timing. While a request is still running, reasoning/tool snapshots and the open tool detail refresh progressively, and switching rows clears the previous request before the new one paints so completed output cannot leak into another live log. Usage/request rows and conversation messages remain, but exact input + request reasoning default to 30-day retention and old per-tool detail to 90 days; env overrides can extend or disable those windows. "Clear all logs" wipes the log history for every profile (confirmation required).
</settings_logs>

<settings_usage>
Token/cost analytics for the active profile. Every profile that can open the Usage tab also sees the live CLI subscription quotas (the shared host machine's plan usage, not per-profile billing); the same numbers surface in the chat input status popover for any profile.
- Range: 24h / 7d / 30d / 90d / All. KPI cards: Requests; Total tokens (NOTE: intentionally EXCLUDES cache reads — it is input+output+thinking minus cached, so cache-heavy numbers look lower here than the per-request "total" in Logs); API-equivalent cost (what all selected-range usage would cost at metered API rates, while subscription-covered traffic remains actually billed as $0); Error rate. Claude Code rows prefer the CLI's own per-model client-side cost estimate, which understands cache reads/writes and multi-step runs. Codex rows use the actual app-server model and official API rates applied per provider call, including long-context thresholds; historical rows that predate this detail use a visibly documented aggregate estimate. The By model table shows subscription traffic as "incl. (≈ $X)" and exposes the estimate method on hover; unknown-pricing models remain excluded. Each KPI shows a delta vs the previous window.
- Charts: tokens per day, API-equivalent cost per day split into metered API vs subscription-included equivalent. Tables: by model, by agent, by tool (calls, failures, avg duration).
- CLI subscription quotas: the Codex card shows live 5-hour and 7-day windows from Codex app-server's account rate-limit API (falling back to the legacy usage endpoint if needed), each with % used, a reset countdown, and a "pace" line (ahead-of-pace = projected to run out early; behind-pace = banked headroom). It also lists Codex "Resets" (earned rate-limit reset credits): how many are available and, per credit, when it expires; the chat status popover shows the same count with the soonest expiry. The Claude Code card shows the same 5-hour and 7-day windows when the CLI's \`/usage\` panel exposes subscription quotas — scraped from the CLI login the app itself spawns first (the one chat actually consumes), with the token-protected host bridge as a fallback for Docker installs whose subscription login lives only on the host. If Claude Code is genuinely on API-key billing (detected from the CLI's own billing banner, not inferred), \`/usage\` only exposes session cost/activity, so the card reports that subscription quota windows are unavailable instead of showing stale or placeholder data; a logged-out host login is reported as exactly that.
</settings_usage>

<settings_updates>
Managed app updates + the Danger zone.
- Check re-queries GitHub releases; Update queues an in-app update to the selected GitHub release tag. Update is only enabled when an update is available, the working tree is clean, the install is "managed", and no update job is already running. A dirty tree ("local file changes") blocks managed updates. During a Docker update a live host-updater log streams in. Docker installs run model work outside the request-serving web container. On generation-aware releases, the updater builds first, boots the inactive blue/green worker on the new image, closes admission only on the old generation, opens the new generation, atomically switches routing, and recreates web immediately. Old accepted trees finish on their pinned image while new jobs use the new code; the old generation is retired only when idle. The blue slot remains as the stable live-browser router when green is current. Background ownership is transferred only after overlap, preventing duplicate schedulers and recovery sweeps, and a shared fleet concurrency lease keeps the single global active-agent cap intact across both workers. A compatibility upgrade from the original worker and standalone/non-Docker installs retain drain-before-restart behavior. The updater also saves the currently-running Docker image as the one-slot cached rollback build, prunes Docker build cache/dangling images without deleting rollback or either in-use generation, rebuilds safely, and reports completion back to the app. Heavy stable layers keep inline cache metadata inside tagged live/rollback images so later builds can reuse them after disposable builder-cache pruning.
- Only the admin profile's chat agent receives the proactive pending-update hint. Member-profile agents are not told that an app release is available; update controls remain governed separately by the profile access matrix.
- Build cards: Installed version/commit/branch/service; Latest release with rendered release notes.
- Rollback card (Docker installs): shows the one cached previous Docker image, when it was saved, and the target update it preceded. "Rollback to cached build" uses the same forward-only blue/green handoff when both live and cached images support it, so new work can start on the cached code while the current generation drains. A rollback to the original durable-worker generation canonicalizes safely to blue; a rollback to an image that predates workers drains all AI work and returns to single-process mode without duplicate schedulers. It is unavailable until an update has saved a previous image and can disappear after a manual \`docker system prune -a\`; managed pruning preserves it.
- CLI tools card (Docker installs): shows the installed Claude Code and Codex CLI versions; "Update CLIs" closes admission and waits for accepted runs because both generations share the CLI home, then performs a coordinated restart. Codex installs/updates use the production-verified 0.144.4 app-server package by default (the host bridge package list remains environment-overridable). "Restart container" drains the current generation, stops every process that could hold a profile DB, makes blue the sole pending-restore/background owner, waits for it to become healthy, then starts web.
- Danger zone → Backup / Restore / Factory reset (see <data_management>).
</settings_updates>
</settings>

<data_management>
All three live under Settings → Updates → Danger zone.

Backup:
- A portable .tar.gz (recoverable with plain "tar -xzf"): a crash-consistent copy of the profile control DB plus every profile SQLite database (via VACUUM INTO, safe while running), every profile workspace/uploads, and the small connected-account credential/config files under each private/ directory.
- Deliberately EXCLUDED (re-link these after a restore): the live WhatsApp companion sessions (Baileys auth state plus the legacy WhatsApp Web browser profile), browser-agent Patchright profiles, the codex CLI home, and the regenerable map-tile cache.
- The user can download one from the UI. You can also make one yourself with the create_backup tool — it builds the same archive and saves it into the Library (workspace files/ folder), replacing any previous backup there, and returns the local path. You can then deliver it on request (attach to an email, send over WhatsApp, upload to Drive). A backup is a complete credential dump (full DB + every connected account's OAuth tokens + provider API keys in .env.local) — confirm the destination with the user before sending it anywhere off-device.

Restore (USER-ONLY — you cannot perform it):
- The user uploads a backup .tar.gz in the UI. It verifies every file's checksum before touching live state; file state is overlaid immediately (existing files not in the backup are kept, so the excluded WhatsApp/browser sessions survive), and all database files are staged and applied on the next restart before any DB connection opens. Direct the user to Settings → Updates → Danger zone → Restore.

Factory reset (USER-ONLY — there is no tool for it, and you must not attempt an equivalent by other means):
- In the UI, behind a typed "delete" confirmation and at least one selected scope. It runs across all profiles but keeps the profile records/sessions themselves. Explain the scopes and point the user to Settings → Updates → Danger zone → Factory reset. Recommend they take a backup first. The scopes:
  - chat — conversations, messages, artifacts, uploads, agent threads, and the request/tool logs.
  - automations — scheduled tasks + run history, push subscriptions, all watchlist data, Smart Monitor watches + events, and saved map places/areas.
  - memory — USER.md, MEMORY.md, MEMORY_ARCHIVE.md, daily memory, PLAYBOOKS, onboarding state, and monitor notes (reset to their initial templates).
  - integrations — every stored OAuth token, the WhatsApp session, the browser-agent profile, and all private integration state.
  - env — .env.local (provider keys, OAuth secrets, service URLs). Flagged destructive.
  - Default selection: chat + automations + memory + integrations. env is OFF by default, so .env.local is preserved unless the user explicitly ticks it.
</data_management>

<integrations_overview>
There are nine integrations (Gmail, Google Calendar, Google Workspace, WhatsApp, Home Assistant, Google Maps, Weather, Location Intelligence, Remote MCP servers), managed in Settings → Integrations and described live in your always-on <integrations> block with their connection state. Their operational tools load on demand (call ActivateIntegrationTools with the id when you need them); activation returns the full doctrine and authoritative compact tool schemas immediately for same-turn use, while later turns carry the doctrine in the normal active-capability block. Setup/lifecycle tools stay behind the setup capability, so activate setup when actually connecting or repairing a service. Gmail setup is profile-aware end to end: GmailStatus/GmailConfigure/GmailStartOAuth run directly in the active profile without local curl, temporary profile cookies, workspace OAuth-state files, or an SSH workaround. Gmail, Calendar, and Drive use the shared \`/api/integrations/google/oauth/callback\` by default, while the legacy Gmail-specific callback remains accepted when explicitly configured. Per-item housekeeping acts in bulk in one call when asked to (e.g. "archive all of these"): the Gmail archive/mark/label/trash/delete tools take an ids array, WhatsApp mark-read/unread take chat_ids, Calendar delete/RSVP/move take event_ids, Drive trash/delete/move take file_ids, and Home Assistant light/cover/climate take entity_ids — one approval covers the batch and the tool reports per-item success/failure. WhatsApp older-message lookup is read-only but deliberately scoped to one chat and bounded by filters/caps; it is for finding message ids/media before download, not for exporting the whole account. Each has a runbook under INTEGRATIONS/<id>.md. Two are keyless/composition-only and gate on activation alone with no connection handshake (Maps, Weather). Remote MCP is generic: configure the endpoint, OAuth if needed, list remote tools, then call exactly one remote MCP tool through RemoteMcpCallTool; mutating/credit/outreach/enrichment actions need explicit user approval. WhatsApp is the one integration whose operational tools are always exposed (but writes still require explicit confirmation) — don't describe gating as perfectly uniform. Default member profiles can connect their own Gmail, Google Calendar, Google Workspace, WhatsApp, Home Assistant, and Maps setup; admin can also share existing Gmail/Calendar/Workspace/WhatsApp/Home Assistant connections to them from Settings → Profiles. These are independent toggles: own only, shared only, or both. Gmail, Google Calendar, Google Workspace, WhatsApp, and Home Assistant tools use the profile's own connection unless an accessible shared connection has been explicitly selected as that profile's default; a grant alone makes the connection available for selection but does not become the runtime source. Shared access never copies the owner's secrets. Maps/Weather use personal profile keys or inherited admin API keys rather than per-account shared connection rows. For the full operating doctrine of a given integration or subsystem, activate it; this guide is the map, not the deep manual.
</integrations_overview>

<feature_mechanics>
Concise mechanics for the questions users actually ask. Activate the specific subsystem (watchlist / scheduling / monitoring) for its full operating doctrine before configuring one.

Watchlist:
- Tracks financial instruments (stocks, ETFs, indexes, FX, crypto — live quotes + candlestick charts) and products (price observations you record over time + a price-history line). Add by symbol search or a product URL.
- Market data comes from Twelve Data and needs TWELVE_DATA_API_KEY (or MARKET_DATA_API_KEY). Without it: only a few built-in example symbols show, no live quotes/search/history.
- IMPORTANT: adding something to the Watchlist does NOT start background alerts. Background price monitoring is one consolidated system task ("Markets monitor") on a FIXED 5-minute cadence (never reschedule it) that ARMS only when the market-data key is set AND at least one item/alert is explicitly monitor-enabled; otherwise it stays paused. Each tick is pure code (no model) and only wakes the agent on an actual threshold crossing, then once for all movers together.

Scheduling:
- Run work later. Action types: "tool" (a single deterministic tool with args resolved at creation — cheap, no model at fire time), "agent" (wakes a model with your prompt at fire time), and "monitor" (system-managed, read-only in the form — the markets/smart/microscripts heartbeats).
- Schedule kinds: In (relative once), At (absolute once), Daily at, Weekly on, Every (interval ≥1 min), Cron (with timezone). Per task: enable/disable, Run now (doesn't consume a one-shot), Past runs history, Delete.
- A one-shot overdue by more than ~5 min (e.g. app was down) is marked "missed" and not auto-run on its original schedule; instead the agent is woken to judge whether doing it late still makes sense — benign/idempotent actions may be completed, stale or risky ones are surfaced for the user to decide. If a one-shot fails when it fires, the agent is likewise woken to recover (retry transient errors, fix the cause, or explain with next steps). Completed/missed/failed one-shots are kept briefly for visibility, then auto-removed (their Inbox results persist). Adaptive self-pacing is opt-in: a fixed-cadence task the user chose stays fixed; only adaptive agent tasks may reschedule themselves. Results are silent by default — they reach the Inbox only when the run calls notify_inbox, on error, for one-shot confirmations, or when Run-now is used.

Smart Monitor:
- One always-on, model-owned monitor that pings the user only when something matters. Nothing is watched by default. The "/monitor" page has three tabs: Watches, Microscripts, Webhooks. Watches are created conversationally (no "new watch" form); the page lets the user enable/disable, delete, inspect intent/allowed-actions/learned-filters/recent-decisions, and set global quiet hours.
- Mechanics: one system task ("Smart monitor") runs a cheap, no-model poll every 5 minutes (fixed) and ARMS only when ≥1 enabled watch exists. The poll buffers genuinely-new matches; right before a buffered match would wake the AI, source adapters that support it do a final freshness recheck and drop items the user has already handled (for example a Gmail message that is no longer unread, or a WhatsApp chat whose unread badge cleared). Gmail pending items also read the relevant message body at this pre-wake point, keeping the 5-minute poll cheap while giving the agent real message text (HTML converted to text with links preserved where possible) when it is about to judge or notify. The AI agent is woken only when there's still something pending and a minimum gap has elapsed (adaptive: min wake gap defaults to ~15 min, a safety ceiling to ~6 h, bounded between the 5-min poll and 24 h). The agent tunes its own pacing via task_state, not the schedule. Connector adapters may add their own load-shaping inside that heartbeat; WhatsApp in particular treats a stored Baileys session as resumable, skips until its next jittered window, backs off during quiet periods, varies bounded chat/message limits, and shares the same serialized operation guard as manual WhatsApp reads so it does not perform the same read pattern or collide with user-triggered reads on every heartbeat. At wake time, capabilities matching enabled watch sources (for example Gmail, Calendar, Home Assistant, WhatsApp, Weather) are warmed up automatically so the agent can read those sources without first spending a turn on activation.
- WhatsApp monitor events expose message type plus has-text/has-media predicates, so empty protocol/technical events can be suppressed without hiding real media-only messages.
- Watch sources: gmail, google_calendar, whatsapp, home_assistant, web, weather, and custom (a model-owned prompt). Each watch has an allowed-actions permission boundary (notify_inbox is always allowed; anything else — gmail_archive / mark_read / label / send-or-forward, ha_call_service, a templated WhatsApp reply — is opt-in, valid only on a watch of the matching source, and engine-enforced; gmail_send is the standing authorization for a Gmail watch to auto send/forward email to a confirmed recipient list, e.g. forwarding receipts). A learning loop records "was it worth it?" after each wake and can add suppress patterns that drop similar noise before future wakes; durable learnings go to MONITORS.md. When a Gmail watch explicitly allows gmail_archive, a future match dropped by one of those learned suppress patterns is also removed from Inbox during the cheap pass (thread-first when possible), with success/failure recorded in the watch events; without that standing authorization suppression never changes the mailbox.
- The learning loop also watches what the user DOES with monitor notifications: opening, replying, deleting without reading, and one-click quick actions on an Inbox item are recorded back onto the watches that produced it (visible as "user signal" entries in the watch's recent decisions). Repeatedly dismissed-unread shapes teach the agent to quiet that noise (a suppress pattern or digest demotion, with the reason shown in /monitor); opened/replied shapes stay prompt. There are no hardcoded thresholds — the agent judges, and the user can remove any learned filter from the watch detail panel.
- Closed-loop follow-ups: after an outward action with an expected effect (a sent email awaiting a reply, an invite awaiting an RSVP, a WhatsApp message awaiting an answer), the agent can attach a short-lived follow-up watch ("expecting X by deadline"). It auto-resolves when the effect arrives (the agent confirms the loop closed), escalates to the Inbox if the deadline passes with nothing observed, and removes itself once handled — follow-ups show a "follow-up" badge in /monitor while waiting and never accumulate. They coexist with the integration's main watch.
- Proactive proposals + self-scheduled returns: alerting on a matched item is the floor, not the ceiling. When what the monitor observes adds up to a concrete, actionable suggestion (an emerging pattern, an inferred upcoming date/obligation, an opportunity, a recurring annoyance it could remove), it surfaces a proposal in the Inbox — "I noticed X — want me to Y?" with do-it / not-now / never quick replies — held to the same interrupt bar and the same engagement-learning loop as alerts, so dismissed proposal shapes get quieted just like noisy alerts. And when the useful move is later rather than now, it makes itself come back instead of leaving a note that gets forgotten: a discrete future obligation ("order in 3 days", "a review lands in 5 days") becomes a real scheduled task, while an in-loop revisit just widens the monitor's own wake gap to land at the target time.
- Microscripts run trusted Python with ctx.timezone, ctx.datetime_utc, and ctx.local_time from config.json's timezone. Their sandbox still blocks arbitrary absolute paths, but allows read-only system timezone metadata under /usr/share/zoneinfo so Python ZoneInfo can format local times without hand-coded offsets.
- Microscript agent wakes differ from Smart Monitor wakes mainly in how they are triggered: the script supplies the trigger context, and by default (toolSurface "full") the woken agent gets its normal gated tool surface — any action stays bounded by the action policy and the user's standing authorizations, and the wake is instructed to re-verify the triggering entities before it acts. A script can set toolSurface "read-only" to restrict a wake to context reads plus notify_inbox (judge-and-notify only). Each agent wake has an idle (no-progress) timeout, so a wake whose provider/model goes silent is reaped and records an operation failure instead of holding a concurrency slot or leaving the script running — but an agent that keeps making progress is never cut off mid-work.
- Webhooks tab: create public inbound webhook endpoints (bearer / HMAC-SHA256 / Svix-Standard Webhooks / none auth, secret rotation, rate limit, retention) and subscriptions; webhook events enter a durable, ordered, idempotent delivery queue for subscribed Microscripts, not directly to watches. Bursts are processed serially per subscription, retries survive restarts, and an already-completed event is not delivered twice. The HMAC profile accepts common provider variants such as Shopify/GitHub/Stripe/Slack signatures; the Svix profile covers Resend, Clerk, and senders using svix-* or webhook-* headers.

Smart Maps:
- Full-screen interactive Google map. Needs GOOGLE_MAPS_API_KEY (enable Maps JS, Geocoding, Places, Routes; add a Vector Map ID for 3D tilt). Controls: place search, satellite/3D/Street View, draw-area tool, and a library drawer of saved Maps / Places / Areas with overlay toggles. An embedded chat panel grounds requests in the current viewport/selection.
- The agent paints maps as application/vnd.ant.map artifacts (the MapRender tool, orchestrator-only). Saving places/areas is a UI action. Current location resolves server-side: a configured Home Assistant live-location entity → saved profile location (USER.md) → browser geolocation as a UI fallback.

Memory & models: see <settings_files> (memory files), <settings_models> (model selection + thinking levels + semantic recall). Raw memory remains complete, while prompt views are bounded: the last ~3 app-configured local days are compacted when busy, as are large USER/PLAYBOOKS files; MEMORY stays full within its safety cap. Every saved entry remains represented with omitted spans explicitly pointing back to the raw note. Full compacted files, the cold tier (MEMORY_ARCHIVE.md, off-wake MONITORS.md), older memory history, and prior conversation messages remain reachable by meaning via automatic per-turn recall and memory_search.

Workouts:
- Chat workout requests should become application/vnd.ant.workout artifacts, not plain markdown. The workout capability loads a schema + history doctrine and unlocks GetRecentWorkouts/ListExerciseHistory/GetExerciseHistory plus GetBodyMetrics/SaveBodyMetrics so the model can seed targets from prior sets, read notes/failures/RPE, rotate muscle groups from recent sessions, and read the user's weight/height/BMI/body-fat %/muscle % (asking for them when missing and saving what the user shares) to scale loads and bias volume/intensity to the user's composition and goal. Completed-session history stores each exercise's canonical definition; GetExerciseHistory/ListExerciseHistory return that reusable template plus the verified saved image, so the model preserves the exercise and primarily edits planned sets, load/reps, progression, and prior-session snapshots on later runs. It also unlocks GetExerciseImage/SearchExerciseImages/SaveExerciseImage so the model builds a verified per-exercise demo-image library once (search → visually inspect the exact movement/machine → save by exercise id); there is intentionally no blind renderer fallback.
- The in-surface workout coach prompt includes the active set timer, each saved set's elapsed time when available, and average timed-set pace for the live session, so coaching can react to exercise pacing before the workout is finished. The coach injects that live workout context on every sent message whether it is attached to the workout's original conversation or a blank side conversation.
- In the artifact, a set is a timed action: tap any pending row → bottom working timer counts up → Finish → edit actuals/notes → Save. For holds/cardio/intervals, the finished timer prefills actual duration instead of the planned target. Only Save marks the set complete and starts rest. The next planned set is highlighted as a suggestion, not a lock. Proprietary resistance machines can track numeric load with their own short unit (for example Kinesis “level”) independently of kg/lb. The full-screen workout surface requests a screen wake lock while open and visible, then releases it on hide/unmount; unsupported browsers simply ignore this. Its floating Back/New chat controls remain reachable while scrolling; Back follows history, New chat starts clean, and the per-session scroll position is restored when returning. While a session is active but unfinished, the app stores a tiny current-workout pointer in browser storage and shows a global floating return button outside the workout surface; the button includes rest/set timing and disappears after Finish workout or Discard. Active sessions support ad-hoc extra sets and new straight weighted/bodyweight/resistance exercises, stored as session-local plan additions so they are included when saving; the Add exercise dialog covers push, back/pull, legs/core, and general muscle groups. Rest timers are logged as rest events when skipped, replaced by the next set, completed, or stopped on Finish workout; the rest-bar continue action prefers the same exercise's next unfinished set before falling back to global workout order. Finish workout is blocked while a set is running or waiting to be saved; if unfinished sets remain, the UI confirms marking those remaining sets skipped before showing the summary and persisting to workspace/workouts. Before completion, Finish workout opens a custom feedback dialog for optional notes and 1–5 stars; the feedback is stored with the finished session. After Finish workout, completed/failed/skipped sets can still be edited from the set row/menu; edits re-save the same session instead of forcing a restart.
- Rest timers use absolute start/end timestamps and are included in both immediate browser persistence and server autosave. Backgrounding, reloading, or briefly leaving the app therefore restores the correct remaining time; if it elapsed while away, the bar returns as "Rest done" and stays until Next/Close. A planned 0-second rest is treated as intentional no-rest and never renders a misleading 0:00 bar.
- Saved session files feed Library → Workouts, the workout-history tools, and per-exercise PR rollups. The tools expose actual per-set durations, active-set/rest events, and session/exercise timing summaries so the agent can recommend rest changes, deloads, or pacing adjustments from real session behavior. Body metrics are stored separately under workouts/body-metrics.json, shown on the Workouts tab, and read/written by the agent via GetBodyMetrics/SaveBodyMetrics — it reads them (and asks the user when missing or stale) to scale loads and bias volume/intensity to the user's composition and goal.

Workflow skills:
- Skills are local workflow bundles under the repo's skills/ directory, the app state skills/ directory, or a legacy profile-private skills/ directory (auto-promoted to the app-state global root on boot). The prompt shows only a compact <skills_index>; full SKILL.md instructions, referenced guides, validators, scripts, schemas, and templates load lazily with SkillSearch / ActivateSkill / ReadSkillFile. This keeps Codex and API-backed providers compatible because the Orchestrator tool layer owns discovery and file reads instead of relying on provider-native skill systems.
- Custom skills can be managed from Settings → Integrations → Custom Skills or through the app's settings APIs. They are global shared app state and admin-only to create/edit/delete; custom skills are global-only, and any legacy profile-scoped skill is auto-promoted to the global skills root by a one-time, idempotent boot migration (skipped only when a global skill already owns the id). A global skill with the same id shadows the bundled repository skill of that id. When installing skills found on the web or from Codex/Claude communities, convert them into Orchestrator custom skills; do not place them in CODEX_HOME/.codex/skills, ~/.codex/skills, or ~/.claude/skills because provider-native skill homes are deliberately not the source of truth here.
- Bundled file-workflow skills include pptx, docx, xlsx, and pdf. Use them for PowerPoint decks, Word documents, spreadsheets/CSV/Excel models, and PDF extraction/editing/forms/OCR workflows. The PDF skill requires rendered-page visual QA before delivery when layout matters.
- Bundled analysis/design/operations skills include data-analytics, incident-investigation, product-design-audit, theme-factory, internal-comms, and frontend-design. Data-analytics validates sources, diagnoses metrics, builds evidence-backed visuals/reports, and uses the existing artifact/file/app surfaces; incident-investigation traces the first broken runtime boundary from logs through browser/API/data; product-design-audit captures and inspects product-flow evidence before prioritizing issues. Frontend-design now explores three genuinely distinct visual directions before broad greenfield/redesign implementation, using image_generator mockups when available and an explicit text-direction fallback when it is not; a selected/provided mockup becomes the implementation reference and browser QA compares the result against it. Routine Orchestrator UI maintenance still follows the existing product design system unless the user explicitly asks for exploration or redesign. Theme-factory and internal-comms continue to cover visual themes and format-specific business writing.
- Bundled CAD skills: \`cad\` designs/modifies parametric 3D parts and assemblies from natural language (build123d Python → validated STEP, with STL/3MF/GLB exports and snapshot self-review) and finishes by emitting the application/vnd.ant.cad 3D viewer artifact; \`step-parts\` searches the step.parts catalog for real STEP models of named purchasable components (servos, motors, screws, bearings, boards). The CAD artifact schema + workflow loads via ActivateIntegrationTools("cad").
- Bundled legal skills (in-house counsel workflows, vendored from Anthropic's knowledge-work legal plugin, Apache-2.0): \`legal-review-contract\` (clause-by-clause review against a negotiation playbook with redlines), \`legal-triage-nda\` (GREEN/YELLOW/RED NDA screening), \`legal-compliance-check\`, \`legal-risk-assessment\` (severity×likelihood), \`legal-vendor-check\`, \`legal-signature-request\`, \`legal-response\` (templated replies to DSRs, litigation holds, subpoenas), \`legal-brief\` (daily/topic/incident briefs), and \`legal-meeting-briefing\`. A shared \`legal-workflow-core\` loads once for their evidence, jurisdiction, source-freshness, missing-connector, authorization, privacy, and counsel-review contract instead of repeating that policy in all nine skills. They operate on documents the user provides (upload/paste/Library) — Orchestrator has no CLM/DocuSign/Box/Slack/Atlassian connectors, so steps that assume them fall back to asking for the document or handing back drafted output; Gmail is available. They assist with legal workflows and are explicitly not legal advice. A companion \`legal-romania\` skill localizes all nine to Romanian law (Cod Civil, Codul Muncii, Cod Fiscal, GDPR + Legea 190/2018, consumer, e-signature, the 9-regulator map) via lazily-loaded \`references/*.md\`, and carries a grey-zone / aggressive-but-lawful strategic doctrine (risk-tiered options bounded by the anti-abuz guardrails, stopping at actual illegality); each legal skill activates it when the matter is Romanian and re-verifies volatile fiscal figures with web search at runtime rather than trusting stored numbers.
- Substantial skill-backed deliverables should normally be delegated to worker with the required skill named in the handoff; orchestrator may use a skill directly for small bounded tasks.
</feature_mechanics>

<under_the_hood>
Machinery that runs in code with little or no UI. Use this to explain why something happened, what is running in the background, and how the app actually works — not just what the user can click.

Voice gateway (live voice mode):
- The composer's live voice mode runs through a server-side gateway: the browser streams mic audio over a WebSocket at /api/voice/ws (authenticated by the profile-session cookie), the server holds the Gemini Live connection, executes tools server-side, and streams spoken audio + captions back. In production the custom Node server dispatches the WebSocket upgrade; nothing extra to configure.
- "Automatic" live model selection queries Google's model catalog for live-capable (bidiGenerateContent) models and picks the newest Flash — new live model generations arrive without a code change (cached ~6h).
- The voice agent's Home Assistant calls are code-enforced against the Settings → Voice allowlist; lock/alarm domains are always refused regardless of config. Complex requests go through delegate_to_orchestrator → a background worker agent; when it finishes, the result is appended to the voice conversation, pushed as a notification, and spoken into the live session if it is still open.
- Completed turns persist as normal user/assistant messages; live voice conversations start with a timezone-aware "Voice chat HH:MM" fallback and then auto-name from the first transcript exchange when possible. Sessions auto-resume across Google-side connection rotations (goAway/session limits).

Boot sequence (every app start):
- Before any database opens, any pending backup restore applies every staged DB (control DB + profile DBs) via atomic file swaps — this is exactly why a Restore needs a restart to finish.
- On Docker, web registers request-serving surfaces while every blue/green worker boots a standby-safe leadership watcher. Exactly the generation named as background owner performs interrupted-run reconciliation for EVERY profile, starts the scheduler, and wires system monitor heartbeats; standby/draining workers do not run those loops. Managed updates start the new generation before switching new admission, temporarily leave background ownership empty while old accepted work drains, then promote the new generation. The host bridge automatically completes an interrupted post-cutover retirement on restart, always forward, and web never marks a request interrupted merely because its proxy process restarted. After a real host/process restart, interrupted-stream reconciliation retries transient SQLite writer contention before background startup, so stale work does not continue to look live merely because the first recovery write met a busy WAL. Standalone installs perform the same reconciliation/background boot in their one process. Workspace template files are ensured inside each active profile workspace (untouched scaffolds are left out of your prompt).

Profile runtime:
- A small control DB stores profiles, sessions, profile audit events, integration connection/default-account records, public webhook slug ownership, and bounded owner-agent help requests. The built-in admin/owner profile uses the legacy root .orchestrator state; member profiles live under .orchestrator/profiles/<profileId>/.
- Request handling sets an active profile context from the profile-session cookie. The SQLite proxy, config/env reader, uploads, artifacts, memory, CLI runtimes, browser-agent state, integration token stores, push subscription store, chat streams, SSE events, scheduler, microscripts, and Smart Monitor all resolve paths/data from that active profile.
- Owner-agent help deliberately crosses that isolation boundary only through its narrow request record: the member sends a secret-redacted self-contained brief, the runtime switches into the admin profile for a fresh hidden owner-agent thread, and only the completion tool's redacted minimum response crosses back. It has no attachment/path bridge, cannot turn the request into confirmed_by_user, cannot change profile grants, and uses the admin/owner's Inbox/push path when human input remains necessary.
- Public webhook POSTs do not carry a profile cookie. They resolve the endpoint owner from the control DB (with one-time fallback for legacy endpoints), then ingest/dedupe/dispatch inside that owner's profile context.

Agent concurrency (why a big fan-out doesn't crash the box):
- On Docker, model execution trees live in the durable worker fleet. The web service routes new AI requests to the registry's current generation and owner-sensitive Stop/Steer/research/Browser controls to the generation that accepted them; shared profile databases hold progress snapshots, and chat sync merges events from current plus draining workers so both old completions and new-code turns appear immediately. The blue worker also routes stable VNC URLs to the actual blue/green browser endpoint. One elected worker owns scheduler/monitor/reconciliation machinery. Update/rollback use a race-free generation switch; an arbitrary project-wide \`docker compose up\` is unsupported because it bypasses registry/drain guarantees, while Settings → Updates, the host bridge, restart, rollback, and \`python3 scripts/docker-update-bridge.py --deploy-current\` preserve active work.
- Every agent run — sub-agent delegations, scheduled wakes, Inbox replies, microscript wakes, artifact repairs — shares one global active pool: 12 active agents overall by default, regardless of top-level/nested position or provider (overridable only as a whole with AGENT_TOTAL_CONCURRENCY). There are no main/provider sub-pools and no cumulative per-tree spawn quota: a large tree keeps draining through one queue, so completed agents and jobs merely waiting for admission never consume an active slot; one parallel call still accepts at most 6 jobs and delegation depth remains bounded. Codex/Claude Code retain a separate RAM-derived process-residency safety backstop per delegation depth (overridable with AGENT_MAX_RESIDENT_<PROVIDER>_PER_DEPTH), because a suspended synchronous CLI parent still has a real app-server process in memory even after releasing its active slot. Its automatic floor is the full global cap (12), so it can never reduce active CLI concurrency; it becomes observable only when suspended resident parents accumulate. Fresh starts are staggered and excess active runs queue; Stop removes waiting admissions immediately so cancelled children cannot start later just to abort. Queued cards are persisted, sync snapshots hydrate the live transcript after a reconnect/background wake, and durable streaming checkpoints are rate-limited to about once per second while direct SSE remains token-live, avoiding SQLite/block-write amplification. Durable workers acquire directly from the shared SQLite fleet pool while standalone installs use one in-memory pool, avoiding double-gate hold-and-wait. During a blue/green overlap, the shared fleet lease enforces the same 12-agent global cap and process-memory safety budget across BOTH generations, so an update cannot accidentally double load. Delegating parents and browser tasks waiting for their concrete session release their one active slot and reclaim it before resuming, preserving deadlock freedom.
- A \`delegate_to\`/\`delegate_parallel\` call is structurally synchronous and keeps the parent dormant until its child returns; there is no \`run_async\` switch on either schema. The only early-resume exception is a user-originated live steer: Codex opens a scoped intervention window, and \`manage_delegations list\` exposes the root's \`active_synchronous\` work so it can cancel an obsolete batch or leave it running and return to sleep. Without that explicit steer, early parent content or tool activity still fails closed. Only the depth-0 root receives the separate \`delegate_async\` and \`manage_delegations\` tools. Delegated children can sub-delegate only synchronously, so their results return to that direct parent instead of creating a conversation-level completion wake. Context forwarding is likewise limited to threads created by the same direct parent in the same parent-thread scope; it cannot cross agent branches. A root async launch requires a concrete independent parent slice and arms one completion wake automatically, avoiding polling, repeated short waits, status-check babysitting, or a forgotten detach. Legacy nested wake rows are suppressed during recovery. The main Orchestrator prompt records the user's standing request to use any available runtime specialist, singly or in parallel within runtime limits, whenever delegation is useful; the request authorizes delegation itself but never bypasses scope, safety, or confirmation requirements for the underlying action. Codex-native collaboration is disabled independently at process and thread level (\`multi_agent\`, \`multi_agent_v2\`, and fan-out), while Orchestrator's standing authorization remains in its own prompt and namespaced delegation-tool descriptions. A provider event for a Codex-native collaboration call fails closed, interrupts the turn, and terminates the app-server before it can silently create an implementation-internal tree. Managed Codex session ids carry a policy generation: after either policy changes, an older managed native thread is refreshed once with the app conversation supplied as portable history, ensuring its frozen developer prompt cannot retain obsolete rules; promptless native Coder sessions are left intact. New Codex threads receive Orchestrator dynamic tools through a dedicated namespace configured as direct-only, which keeps them outside yieldable code-mode cells even when the selected model catalog forces code_mode_only. Agent-message deltas are serialized by app-server item and filtered to the active turn before reaching Markdown rendering, preventing two overlapping Codex messages from being interleaved into corrupt text. Codex 0.144.x cannot replace a thread's stored dynamic-tool catalog during thread/resume, so an older thread born with flat tools can still run synchronous delegation inside a Code Mode cell. For that compatibility path, Orchestrator permits and hides only Codex's native exec → wait control reasoning while the child runs; the wait tool remains provider-internal. Codex may also finish streaming the tail of a reasoning item that began before synchronous delegation. Outside the explicit intervention window, any parent content, shell/file/MCP activity, non-wait dynamic tool, or final response that begins while a synchronous delegation is pending still fails closed and interrupts the parent turn before the activity reaches the UI/tool log.

The one background loop:
- One elected generation's scheduler ticks about every 30 seconds (first sweep a few seconds after leadership boot) and is the only active long-lived background loop. On each tick it sweeps every enabled profile in that profile's context. Everything periodic rides on it as a scheduled task. During worker overlap no generation owns it, avoiding duplicate fires; promotion starts it on the new worker without a process restart. Transient SQLite writer contention defers a claim to the next tick without consuming or disabling the schedule.
- A one-shot that fell overdue by more than ~5 minutes while the app was down is marked "missed" and not auto-run; the agent is woken to judge whether doing it late is still sensible and safe (benign actions may complete, stale/risky ones are surfaced for the user). A one-shot that errors when it fires likewise wakes the agent to recover (retry transient failures, fix, or explain). Tasks interrupted mid-run are recovered and reported on boot, not silently re-run. Terminal one-shots (done/missed/failed) are auto-pruned after a short retention window, along with their run history; surfaced Inbox results are kept.

System tasks (created automatically, shown as read-only/system rows in Scheduling, never user-made):
- Markets monitor — Watchlist price monitoring. Fixed 5-minute cadence; arms only when a market-data key AND at least one monitor-enabled item exist.
- Smart monitor — the consolidated monitoring agent. Fixed 5-minute cheap poll; arms only when at least one watch is enabled; wakes the AI adaptively (min/max wake gap). Boot reconciliation self-heals an enabled heartbeat that was stranded without a next run, preserving its task state and buffered digest items. Its AI wake uses a dedicated prompt pack rather than the whole chat/commerce/artifact policy, receives exact active watch records in the wake packet, activates only connector capabilities required by those watches, exposes Inbox/task-state/feedback primitives by default, and may delegate only public research to Researcher. Learned suppress patterns are not count-capped, so accumulating new noise knowledge cannot make a watch unreadable; roughly weekly the agent silently audits them and may batch-remove expired, duplicate, obsolete, invalid, contradictory, or dangerously broad entries while preserving useful durable filters. Watch lifecycle mutation and direct user-question tools stay out of autonomous wakes.
- Microscripts heartbeat — runs due microscripts and recovers stale running scripts that exceeded the watchdog threshold.
- Memory reflection — nightly memory housekeeping at 03:00 in config.json's timezone; reconciles when the app timezone changes. It starts with a size audit of USER.md, MEMORY.md, MEMORY_ARCHIVE.md, MONITORS.md, and PLAYBOOKS.md; hot files are treated as near budget at ~50k chars and over budget at ~60k, so reflection reads full files from disk when prompt context is truncated, moves old-but-still-useful interactive facts into MEMORY_ARCHIVE.md, deletes stale/irrelevant entries, and densifies verbose notes. Besides curating/densifying the durable files, it hunts for workflows the user asked for repeatedly across recent days (via a chronological recent-activity sweep of conversations) and distills them into PLAYBOOKS.md entries so the next ask replays in one step; it also consolidates Smart Monitor engagement learnings into MONITORS.md. It runs silently, with one exception: a brand-new synthesized playbook may surface a single short Inbox note naming its trigger phrase so the learned shortcut is visible and correctable.
- Capability audit — admin-only weekly self-development triage (Monday 04:00 in config.json's timezone; reconciles on timezone change). It reads every profile-scoped AGENT_NEEDS.md — the backlog agents append to (via ReportAgentNeed) whenever a missing capability, broken tool, or runtime/repo gap blocks them — triages each open entry (already-shipped ones it closes with ResolveAgentNeed, including the source profile_id for non-admin entries; stale ones it flags to drop; worthwhile ones it scopes), and posts ONE ranked, evidence-backed Inbox proposal to the admin weighted toward NEW features, with Build/Drop/Dismiss buttons. It only PROPOSES: nothing is implemented until the user clicks Build, which re-wakes the admin orchestrator in that Inbox thread and runs the normal self-development gate (worktree + coder + checks + preview, then a second confirmation before any push/release/deploy). Empty weeks are silent.
- Cost fact worth stating: the markets and smart-monitor polls run as PURE CODE with zero model calls; the AI is woken only when there is a real signal, and then once for everything together. Monitoring is cheap by default.
- Storage retention rides on the existing scheduler once per day (no extra background loop). Database retention deletes only duplicative heavy detail: exact request input + request reasoning after 30 days, scheduled-run reasoning/content-segments/attachment descriptors after 30 days while preserving each run's summary/status, and per-tool rows after 90 days while preserving request-level counts/usage. Conversation messages, request/usage rows, costs, task definitions, and scheduled-run summaries remain. Filesystem retention runs in a locked child process so scanning/removing large trees cannot stall chat: top-level entries under each profile's workspace/tmp are removed after the ENTIRE entry tree has been untouched for 14 days; a .orchestrator-keep marker anywhere inside it or a sibling <name>.keep file pins it. Isolated project runs are eligible after 30 days only when their durable result is already terminal (pushed or published-static), the repo is git-clean, no owned preview process is active, the repo path is inside its run directory, and the run is not pinned. Prepared/committed-but-unpushed, dirty, active, malformed, or explicitly pinned runs are always preserved. Automatic linked-worktree cleanup keeps its branch in the source checkout; a standalone repo is first archived as a verified Git bundle and is not removed if that archive step fails. Both paths retain a small run-state audit record. Codex runtime retention is reference-aware rather than selective-memory cleanup: after 30 days it can hard-delete at most 200 unreferenced session threads per daily pass through Codex's own thread/delete API, while every thread still named by any profile conversation/agent thread, every recent thread, missing/unknown rollout, and every parent with a protected descendant survives. Both normal and Codex maintenance launches honor an exclusive runtime lock, and a pass skips rather than competing with an already active Codex app-server. Codex's log database keeps its vendor-managed logical retention; when at least 256 MiB and 20% of that file are reusable pages, the locked maintenance pass can compact it (only with enough temporary disk headroom). Use project-run:run/self-dev:run pin|unpin for intentional long-lived runs; storage:maintenance is dry-run by default and requires --apply to mutate. Overrides: ORCHESTRATOR_EXACT_LOG_RETENTION_DAYS, ORCHESTRATOR_SCHEDULED_RUN_DETAIL_RETENTION_DAYS, ORCHESTRATOR_TOOL_LOG_RETENTION_DAYS, ORCHESTRATOR_PROJECT_RUN_RETENTION_DAYS, ORCHESTRATOR_WORKSPACE_TMP_RETENTION_DAYS, ORCHESTRATOR_CODEX_SESSION_RETENTION_DAYS, ORCHESTRATOR_CODEX_SESSION_DELETE_LIMIT; a retention-days value of 0 disables that class. General app SQLite files reuse freed pages immediately and are not automatically vacuumed during live traffic; only the isolated Codex log compaction above runs under its dedicated no-traffic lock.

Memory that works without anyone touching it:
- The HOT durable files are injected by priority: USER.md and MEMORY.md first; MONITORS.md is also prioritized on Smart Monitor/Microscript wakes; the integration index and PLAYBOOKS.md follow; only then is recent daily memory added. Raw files are never rewritten or selectively discarded for prompt size. Large USER, MONITORS, and PLAYBOOKS files receive deterministic extractive views (~28k/~30k/~18k), and the last ~3 MEMORY_DAY files share a ~30k prompt budget. Every parsed entry is represented using its beginning and ending plus an explicit raw-file pointer; monitor wake packets separately carry the exact active runtime watch records. This prevents verbose profile/procedure/day entries from pushing canonical rules out of context. Any compacted source remains eligible for automatic recall. MEMORY_ARCHIVE.md and off-wake MONITORS.md remain cold. The ENTIRE raw memory history and prior user-visible conversations are indexed for semantic search in a derived SQLite index that self-heals through content-hash diffing. Conversation history is indexed as user→assistant EXCHANGES, not isolated messages. If MEMORY or another durable source overflows its safety backstop, the dropped detail stays recall-reachable and nightly reflection treats it as a cleanup signal.
- Prompt budgeting also uses the selected model's context-window metadata when available. The builder measures the assembled system prompt plus the exact exposed tool schemas and keeps them under a conservative ~55% share, shrinking only workspace views in a bounded second pass; the rest stays reserved for conversation history, attachments/tool results, reasoning, and the answer. Large-context models keep the normal rich views, while smaller models degrade explicitly toward raw recall instead of overflowing unpredictably.
- Each turn the user's message is embedded and the most relevant memory NOT fully present in context is injected as a recalled-memory hint (automatic, fail-open, killable with ORCHESTRATOR_MEMORY_RECALL=off). Because recent daily files are represented only compactly, their complete raw entries remain eligible for automatic recall instead of being excluded merely because the date is recent. The semantic index represents every non-template saved memory entry, including short facts, and splits oversized capsules/exchanges into bounded chunks without truncating their tails; chunker upgrades compare old/new chunk text and re-embed only changed sources, keeping the previous vectors until each replacement succeeds. The pass excludes the current conversation because that history is already in the live prompt, then applies a strict threshold, coverage gates, and short in-conversation repeat suppression so marginal notes do not keep resurfacing on consecutive similar messages. When several hits are versions of the same topic, the pass resolves them instead of repeating them: a curated note (durable file or daily ledger — the agent rewrites those in place) outranks raw conversation versions of the same fact, and when only raw versions exist the newest is shown with the older one folded into the same hint, dates visible, so the model judges which still holds. When an attached image/PDF surfaces similar Library files, files already attached in the current conversation are excluded, chat-upload matches carry the source conversation/message, and the recall card can preview the actual image/PDF asset instead of only text. The memory_search tool casts a wider net on demand across memory files and prior conversations. Embeddings reuse the Gemini key (no separate billing). For repeatable calibration, \`memory:eval\` reads a private labeled JSON dataset and reports raw R@4/MRR, automatic recall/precision, negative silence, and a comparable score without syncing the index unless \`--sync\` is explicitly supplied.

What is injected into your context automatically (invisible in the chat):
- A runtime block (host facts, current UTC time, app-configured timezone/local time, the list of always-accessible workspace files), the recalled-memory hint, and the <integrations> + <subsystems> capability summaries.
- Only the CURRENT message's attachments are handed to you inline — older uploads are not, which is the whole reason find_past_uploads exists.
- Uploads are read-only originals stored outside the agent workspace. To edit, convert, or extract from any uploaded file (audio, video, image, PDF, Office, archive), the agent first stages a copy inside the workspace with copy_upload_to_workspace (orchestrator + worker + researcher), works on the returned workspace-relative \`path\` (e.g. Bash ffmpeg), and never modifies the original upload in place — it keeps serving the chat attachment and its previews.

Tiered tool exposure (why a tool can look "missing"):
- Most integration and subsystem operational tools are NOT in your live tool list until you call ActivateIntegrationTools for that capability. Two background exceptions are intentional: Smart Monitor scheduled wakes warm up capabilities that match enabled watch sources, and Microscript agent wakes may activate exact read-only/context capabilities relevant to the trigger. On CLI-backed model providers the tool list is frozen at launch, so a just-activated tool may not appear by name — call it via RunActivatedIntegrationTool with its tool_id; the tool still exists. Never tell the user a capability is missing over this. Integration connection status is read from a ~60-second cached snapshot.
- Profile/integration administration tools are a subsystem too: activate profile_admin only when the active admin profile explicitly asks you to manage profile access, such as granting Home Assistant access to another profile. Non-admin profiles cannot run those tools, and write actions require explicit user confirmation arguments.
- Orchestrator-owned skills are different from provider-native skills/plugins: they are visible through <skills_index> and the SkillSearch / ActivateSkill / ReadSkillFile tools, gated by the profile's Skills permission, and usable by orchestrator + worker across Claude Code, Codex, and API providers. Coder defaults to Claude Code and stays native and toolless when routed to either CLI, but API-backed coder runs receive Orchestrator workspace tools plus the same skill tools.
- Native CLI skills/plugins are kept off in headless Orchestrator runs. Claude Code runs with \`--disable-slash-commands\` and Codex is launched with apps/plugins/skills feature flags disabled, and Orchestrator does not call native skills/list, plugin/list, or plugin/install. This keeps marketplace/plugin state out of agent behavior; use Orchestrator integration tools or Orchestrator-owned workflow skills for specialized work.
- Managed Orchestrator/worker runs on Codex or Claude Code use Orchestrator's permissioned workspace tools instead of native filesystem/shell built-ins, so ListEnvVars → Bash(env_keys) is the same callable path the prompt describes. Their command child environment is an allowlisted runtime base plus only explicitly requested env_keys — it does not inherit the web/worker process's entire secret environment. The promptless Coder is the deliberate exception: it keeps the CLI's native code tools for repository work. Native built-ins are still filtered through the active profile's read/write/shell/web permissions before provider launch.

Logging, naming, audio, push:
- Every model call is logged in the active profile DB (request + reasoning + tool calls). The compact JSONL runtime run/log index is profile-scoped too, so read_runtime_index cannot expose another profile's scheduled runs or model-log previews. Admin Logs aggregates those profile logs through its explicit admin-only path; Usage "Total tokens" deliberately excludes cache reads.
- Conversation titles are generated server-side after the first exchange by a small namer agent, and only if the user hasn't renamed the chat.
- Pure app-recorded voice notes (origin=voice_recording and no typed text in that same user message) get an automatic understanding/transcription pre-pass (the audio-context agent) before your main turn when the main model cannot read audio natively. Uploaded audio files, WhatsApp/downloaded audio, and voice notes accompanied by typed text do NOT auto-pre-pass; the orchestrator sees the attachment and decides whether to listen directly, inspect/convert it, or call TranscribeAudio. For a written transcript as a deliverable, for a voice note the user sent in an earlier message, or when a sub-agent hits audio, there is the TranscribeAudio tool (orchestrator + worker + researcher). It takes upload_ids and/or workspace-relative paths (for audio converted/extracted in the workspace — e.g. copy_upload_to_workspace a video, ffmpeg out the audio track, then transcribe the result), uses the separate Audio Transcript Agent for verbatim transcript mode, uses the Audio Context Agent only for analysis/report mode, and recognizes audio stored under a wrong/missing extension as well as audio-only MP4 containers (an "audio message" with no video track transcribes directly). Gemini-incompatible audio containers are converted to WAV automatically when ffmpeg can decode them; if that fails, the tool tells you to stage the upload, convert it manually with ffmpeg to 16 kHz mono WAV, and retry TranscribeAudio with the converted path. If your own model already reads audio that is in front of you, just listen — no tool call needed.
- Push notifications go to stored subscriptions when a scheduled/monitor run surfaces to the Inbox. Autonomous/background runs that hit a real system blocker should not only write AGENT_NEEDS; when notify_inbox is available they also post one concise Inbox alert with the user impact and what can be retried next.

Steering follow-ups, async delegation, and tracked background jobs:
- A message sent while a turn streams renders as a regular user bubble pinned directly above the composer instead of being inserted prematurely into the transcript. The app tries LIVE injection first: when the running engine accepts mid-turn input (Codex turn/steer), the pending bubble clears and the text lands inside the in-flight turn immediately — persisted as a tagged user row rendered inline at its injection point with a "Steered message" label. Otherwise it remains in the tray as queued and runs as the NEXT turn as soon as the in-flight one ends; only when that turn is actually claimed does it move into normal transcript history. Pending state follows server queue events and runtime snapshots, so refresh/recovery/another tab cannot turn a follow-up into an overlapping normal send. Concurrent starts are queue-safe and never abort the active turn implicitly. The connected app usually starts a queued turn itself (live streaming); if no client is around (phone locked mid-run), a server sweep runs it headlessly within seconds and the result is in the conversation on return. Stop clears the queue on both sides and leaves any not-yet-run text as plain history (already-injected steers are part of the active turn's history).
- Async delegation: only the depth-0 root orchestrator receives \`delegate_async\`, and only when it supplies a concrete different \`independent_parent_work\` slice to execute immediately. One call launches 1-6 jobs, returns the batch/job/persistent-agent-thread ids without suspending the root, and automatically sets \`wake_on_complete\`. One muted completion notice resumes the original task through the follow-up/headless-wake path after all jobs settle unless the root already collected the terminal result. \`manage_delegations\` lists/collects state, supports one intentional bounded wait (up to 5 minutes) only for a concrete same-turn dependency, handles old explicit-detach rows, and cancels obsolete batches. Collecting or timing out while a batch is still running does not accidentally disarm its wake. Delegated children never receive either async tool and nested launches are rejected defensively. Terminal batch/job bookkeeping is pruned after 14 days; the specialist's durable conversation/result remains in its normal agent thread.
- Background jobs: Bash run_in_background and the start_background_job tool start a tracked job OWNED BY THE SERVER, recorded in the profile DB with a redacted log file. On Docker installs, secret-free jobs run in their OWN ephemeral container (started through the host update bridge, image and mounts cloned from the running app) — those jobs survive app restarts AND app updates, and the container disappears when the job ends; jobs with injected secrets, non-Docker installs, or a missing/old bridge fall back to a detached server-owned process. Either way the job survives the end of the agent turn (on CLI runtimes the native runtime would otherwise kill background tasks seconds after the turn ends; on Claude Code runs the native run_in_background parameter is additionally blocked by a hook that redirects to the tracked tool). Background timeouts default to 30 minutes and cap at 24 hours regardless of which tool started the job. When the job exits — or fails to spawn at all — a completion notice (exit code + log tail, rendered as a muted system card) is posted into the owning conversation through the follow-up queue: a streaming turn sees it right after finishing, an idle conversation is woken headlessly so the agent continues the task on its own. Agents can also block on a job with manage_background_jobs action 'wait' (up to 5 minutes) and consume the result in the same turn — then no separate notice is posted. Deliberate kills don't wake. While a job runs, the chat shows a small tray row above the composer (expand for command, elapsed time, log tail, Stop), and Settings → Logs has a "Background jobs" section listing running + recent jobs with a log viewer and Stop. Finished job records and their logs are pruned automatically after 14 days.
- Self-development recovery: run state records the owning profile/conversation. After a host or container restart, the app detects the newest recent dirty self-dev run whose preview was killed, preserves the same worktree, restarts its managed preview, and wakes the original conversation to continue the existing verification/approval gate. It never revives every old run at once and never treats a dead preview PID as permission to discard code.

Other moving parts:
- Webhooks: POST /api/webhooks/<slug> is a PUBLIC inbound endpoint authenticated by the endpoint secret; the slug is owned by one profile; events are deduped/normalized and durably queued for ordered, retryable, idempotent dispatch to that profile's Microscripts (not directly to watches).
- The browser agent drives a real Patchright profile. Browser lifecycle is isolated per app profile: each profile owns a separate persistent cookie/login profile, browser process manager, live-control channel, downloads area, and headful/virtual display. Browser runs are serialized only within the same profile, so two different profiles can run browser agents concurrently in separate virtual windows without sharing tabs, sessions, or authenticated state. Web uploads are UI-first: it opens the site's visible upload/import surface, clicks the intended visible chooser, and the runtime binds one or more explicitly authorized workspace files to the chooser opened by that exact click — avoiding native OS pickers, hidden runtime paths, and ambiguity when a page has many file inputs. Visible dropzones have a separate managed file-drop path; direct file-input attachment remains a guarded fallback and rejects dormant inputs in closed/hidden UI. Every batch is fully sandbox-validated before selection, and the agent must verify filename/preview/progress/success in the page because selection or dropping alone is not proof the site accepted it. File selection may begin transfer immediately, so the exact files/destination and final Import/Upload/Send remain subject to the normal confirmation boundary. WhatsApp keeps provider-specific companion state per profile (Baileys by default, or legacy Chromium WhatsApp Web with \`WHATSAPP_PROVIDER=wwebjs\`); those live sessions remain excluded from backups.
- On Docker installs, app updates and rollback are performed by a host-side updater service OUTSIDE the container (Settings → Updates talks to it, asks it to install the target release tag or switch back to the cached previous image, and streams its log). The updater also prunes Docker build cache/dangling images around rebuilds so repeated Settings updates do not fill the host disk while preserving the tagged rollback image. The CLI subscription usage numbers in the Usage tab are scraped live from that host.
- Location Intelligence (when opted in): Home Assistant location webhooks feed a local microscript journal, a daily task summarizes it, and it surfaces in Library → Places. Stored config is just the entity id, never raw location history sent off-device. The daily task also writes a geo-temporal day journal — a narrative markdown recap weaving location stops with that day's calendar events, notable email, message activity, and geotagged photos — shown under the map on the Places day view and readable by the agent from days/<date>.json (so "what did I do last Tuesday?" gets a real answer). Photos uploaded to the app that carry EXIF GPS are appended to the journal's points automatically (event "photo", pinned to capture time) — only while Location Intelligence is enabled.
</under_the_hood>

<host_and_runtime>
You already receive the STATIC machine facts every turn in your context: host_os, host_hostname, host_arch, node_version, the app origin / public URL, runtime IPv4 candidates, SSH host candidates, and the OAuth-tunnel template. Answer "what machine / what IP / what OS / what's the URL" straight from there — no tool needed.

For LIVE numbers that change, call host_status (it activates together with this guide): free disk space on the key filesystems (state dir, workspace, /tmp), memory pressure, host and process uptime, load average, network interfaces. Lead with disk when the user is worried about space — this app commonly runs in a container whose state dir and /tmp sit on a small host filesystem, and host_status flags any watched filesystem over 85% full. For anything host_status can't reach (docker, systemd, a full df, host package state), use Bash. For an SSH command that specifically needs sudo, remote_sudo first tries non-interactive sudo and only then answers its private marker from a named environment secret; the secret value is never placed in command arguments and is redacted from live/result logs.
</host_and_runtime>
</app_guide>
`
